title: Tough to build, but worth it

The instructions are wordless and made up of endless complex pictures of pieces of wood, plastic, and a million variations of screws and nails. Once you get through the building process, the kitchen itself is beautiful. It has lovely detailing and the neutral tone makes it not a total eye sore in your home. My toddler loves making us meals and washing the dishes in the sink. Something to note - kitchen does not come with any food/pots and pans/accessories.

title: Perfect play kitchen for that area you want to keep ...
text: Perfect play kitchen for that area you want to keep looking a bit more "grown up."  We have this in our elegantly decorated living room and it blends in beautifully for us, gets tons of compliments from guests and best of all... our son loves it.  We have had it for nearly a year now (my son is 19 months right now) and he still plays with it daily.  He loves opening the cupboards, taking things out and putting things in.  He really enjoys pretend talking on the kitchen's little phone.  We added the Doug and Melissa stainless steel kitchenware set ([[ASIN:B00CPHX6YI Melissa & Doug 8-Piece Stainless Steel Pots and Pans Playset for Kids]]) and it goes perfectly with this.  It's quite sturdy compared to similar kitchen sets (I looked at a lot.) I was worried the knobs etc would come loose over time but they have all held up nicely.  After much toddler play, this is still looking new.

title: Love it.  Assembly instructions leave a lot to be desired
text:
I purchased the Uptown KidKraft Kitchen in the ‚Äúnatural‚Äù finish. I want to start by saying this kitchen is awesome! I got it for my daughter‚Äôs 3rd birthday present and she was ecstatic. My 5 year old daughter also likes playing with it. One of the reasons I picked this set was because of the height; it‚Äôs considered a ‚Äúlarge‚Äù kitchen set and is taller than some of the comparable kitchen sets which was important to me because both my girls are on the tall side. The details on the kitchen set are great, including the fact that the oven and stove top knobs turn and click, the water faucet handle moves, there‚Äôs actually a fridge and a freezer, the burners on the stove top are realistic, and there‚Äôs even a towel rack. The product was well packaged and arrived promptly. Even with the good packaging there were two damaged pieces. Luckily it did not affect assembly (as I procrastinated and didn‚Äôt put it together until the night before her birthday) and KidKraft promptly sent me the replacement parts to change out the damaged pieces.
The main disadvantage to the kitchen set is the amount of time it takes to put together; it took me 3&1/2 hours to complete. For the most part I assembled it by myself; I did need some help at the end to hold pieces in place as I put the top pieces on. Part of the long assembly time has to do with the poor instructions; they are pictures only, no words. And the pictures aren‚Äôt very detailed/accurate so sometimes you are not sure what end or side of the board you are working on or which step you should start with. Also some of the screws/fasteners have colored tops (as they go on the outside of the kitchen set) and others are silver. But they are marked with the same letter. So unless you have a vision of what it‚Äôs going to look like it can be hard to determine if you should use the colored screws/fasteners or the silver screws/fasteners. There was one place that didn‚Äôt quite line up correctly which is the top edge/side panel where the dishwasher is, it sticks out slighter farther than the counter top. But it‚Äôs pretty minor and not enough of a blemish/issue to have me take away a star from my review.
I am so glad I purchased this kitchen. It is sturdy and has great detail and both my kids have played with it every day since it was given.

I set aside a couple hours to put it together. Ended up taking me over 4 hours. There are so many little details to assemble it just simply takes time. Nothing too hard. Screws went in fine and I had no big problems. It looks exactly like the picture.

One word of advice. The screws and such come carded and lettered/numbered. The one set of screws has brown heads and the regular metal heads. No where did I see that I was told to use brown heads or regular heads. Had I seen this I wouldn't have opened the metal screws and wondered why they didn't match the color of the wood. Wasn't till I put 6 or so in that I realized there were the same ones painted brown on the other side of the package!

Kids loved it. Simple as that.

title: Pros and cons
text:
Pros: good quality, sturdy, nice looking, lots of storage, kids love it.

They are just painted on and the kids seem to have more fun with the working buttons on other toys and kitchens. It also seems quite small; I think my kids will be too big to enjoy by 6/7 years old.

title: Wonderful play kitchen!
text:
This is a gorgeous-looking, very realistic, very detailed and well-made kitchen! It's so cool that I want to play with it myself! Ours didn't have any broken or defective parts on arrival and was very easy to put together, with clear instructions, though it did take a while. I'm very handy and had a helper (my mom) and it still took me about 4 hours. So, be prepared to spend a good hunk of time putting it together. It arrives completely disassembled into a million pieces, but it comes together easily. For some parts it does require two people. I guess you could do it alone, but it would be very awkward and difficult. For some things, one person needs to hold the part level while the other puts the screws in, for example, and you just need more than two hands. So keep that in mind.

I'm very impressed by the level of detail on this kitchen. Other similar kitchens have just a big sticker where the water/ice dispenser is on the fridge door, with the dispenser as a picture on the sticker, but this one has an actual nook with buttons above it (they don't press down, unfortunately, but it's still better than picture buttons!) The knobs on the stove make fun clicking sounds when you turn them. I see that they've updated the phone now - in older pictures it looks like an older kitchen phone, but now it has been updated to what looks like a white iPhone. I guess that's what the kids of today will associate with the word "phone", so it makes sense.

I absolutely love that the kitchen has a realistic, elegant look. It matches our real kitchen perfectly, because we have stainless steel appliances and dark wood cabinets, so it looks great in it. It looks like a part of the kitchen, not like the total eyesores that a lot of other play kitchens are - ugly and plastic and in horrible bright pink colors. This is something I wouldn't mind actually having in my home and looking at every day. It's beautiful!

This is just a kitchen though, it doesn't come with any cookware or play food. I prefer that, so I don't have to pay additional money for gear I may not like. Everybody can buy their own accessories as they see fit. But if you don't have any yet, definitely do get accessories before presenting it to the child, so they can actually play with it. Not much you can do with just the kitchen. I got a set of pots and pans, a serving set (dishes, utensils and a tea pot), and a couple of sets of play food, including the kind that you can cut (that was a big hit, highly recommend!) and topped it off with a toy high chair for the dolls, and the whole thing was a huge success with my 2-year-old. We've had it for almost a month now and she plays with it every day, for most of the day! If you don't have anywhere nearby to sit a doll down, I do recommend a doll high chair, as well as some sort of little table to serve food on. I didn't want anything big or expensive, so I got a cheap little folding beach table that works perfectly for dolls. The kitchen, the accessories and the chair and table together make for endless hours of play!

There are only a couple of things I wish were a little different, but they're all very minor. I wish the ice/water dispenser nook was a little deeper. Most toy cups don't fit and keep falling out (my daughter keeps putting them down inside the nook instead of holding them while the "water" pours in). There's plenty of room inside the refrigerator, so they could've made the space a little deeper... Same goes for the microwave - it's too shallow and plates don't fit in it, only small bowls and the saucers of the tea cups. There's plenty of room, they could've made it just an inch or two deeper. And lastly, the bar that holds the towel isn't attached to its holders, but just loosely slides inside the holes and rests in them. It's really easy to bump it and then it slides out and falls down. That's easily fixable though - I glued it in place with hot glue and now it stays put. That's all - nothing major, it's a great kitchen!

UPDATE: We've had this kitchen for a year and a half now. We got it right around the time when our second child was born. He's 18 months old now and his sister is 3 and a half, and they both absolutely adore this kitchen!!! Don't look at the recommended age - any age child can play with it! Our baby loved opening and closing the doors as soon as he could crawl over to them, before he could even walk. Then he loved pulling up to stand on the kitchen, and standing and playing on it. Now he's old enough to actually pretend cook, and this is his favorite play area in the whole house! He loves putting cups in the microwave and saying "milk beep beep!". It's absolutely adorable. So don't discount younger kids! I now feel bad for my daughter because I didn't think to get this for her sooner. She was a ripe old 2 when we bought it... She could've enjoyed it so much longer. Oh well. The two of them will be playing with this awesome kitchen for many years to come!

title: Solid construction, great looks, and a ton of fun. (once it's assembled)
text:
My parents bought this for my daughter's 4th birthday and it was a huge hit. It looks beautiful, is very sturdy, and without being battery operated, it stimulates her imagination a great deal. I think that's something most modern toys fail to do these days: let the kid PLAY.

I will warn you, though: If you are not very good at following assembly directions and using hand tools, find another product. This kitchen took myself and my stepfather almost 2 hours to assemble. He's a maintenance mechanic who works on hydraulic systems and the like for a living, so that's saying a lot. Every single piece of this kitchen gets screwed into another piece one way or another. The hardware comes in a huge blister pack and each type of screw is labeled, but it is easy to get mixed up, especially when the directions are somewhat confusing and sometimes seem out of order altogether. Most of the actual furniture in our home was much, much easier to assemble. If this didn't scare you away, good luck, and enjoy. It really is worth the trouble in the end, since the finished product is awesome.

title: BEAT PLAYROOM INVESTMENT!!!
text:
These kitchens are the bees knees. It's worth the expense if you're wanting a nice kitchen. We wanted to purchase a kitchen, but didn't want the old ugly plastic toy kind. This is a perfect fit.

They spared no details. This is great, but expect to assemble for at least a good chunk of morning. If it's a gift make sure to plan when you might assemble it. You'd kids will not want to wait until this is built. It takes some real time.

There are fun details I like that KidKraft didn't spare. The paper towel holder is awesome. We used a real roll and I expected my kids to unravel the whole thing, but they ended up liking taking their own towel to wipe their hands.

It has hooks behind the oven to hang mitts and whatever else. We got pot holders and oven mitts at the dollar store. They work great.

The chalk board works and cleans easily.

It has a phone that looks like an iPhone, my kids love this. They pretend to call everyone they can think of. It has a nice little holder which has been great for keeping track of it.

The trays in the oven and dishwasher are removable. My kids enjoy making play picnics on them or serving me food. I like its dual purpose.

This will last long past your kids. So know it'll last and likely be able to be handed down or sold when they grow up.

It does not include food or pans, so be sure to consider that when purchasing. You can find food and pans for cheap on Amazon as well.

title: You can do it!
text:
Assembly is tedious and is a true act of love. I am a mom and put it together with a #2 phillips screwdriver and the two basic tools provided with the kitchen. The box was heavy but not so much that I couldn't lift it into the house. Assembly took several hours and was rather frustrating at times due to reading the diagrams and making sure I had the parts facing in the right directions but it was not that difficult. Nothing is pre-assembled meaning none of the door nobs or even simple latches etc come attached. I think this so that the pieces will be flatter and compact for shipping.
You should definitely take an inventory of all the parts by putting them in numerical order before beginning so that it is easier to grab a part when assembling, and also so that you know if anything is missing in the shipment. I was missing the 4 knobs that are for hanging any pots, pans and cooking utensils to the back wall. Luckily, this doesn't affect the assembly of the kitchen itself or I would have been very upset. I called Kidkraft and the message said all the operators were busy and to leave a message. There is no phone queue to wait for an agent. This was frustrating but I got a call back an hour or so later and the agent said the knobs would be shipped priority as I live in HI and regular mail would take too long which was nice.Also, there is no part 27. The agent said sometimes a number is skipped for some reason.
The latches for the microwave did not align perfectly as the pre-drilled holes were a bit off but I bent the latch a little to compensate. Also, the top piece of the top shelf was measured a bit off as it sticks out an extra half inch or so in the back than the rest of the kitchen but it's no biggie.
The kitchen is sturdy and seems to be of quality. My 22 mo old likes it and she is now washing dishes on the regular. (I bought her the green toys dish set). She also likes talking on the phone. She can't yet reach the top storage shelf but will grow into that very soon. The size of the kitchen is good- I don't have a big place but it fits nicely in it.
Room for improvement- I wish the fridge, dishwasher, and maybe the oven were a different color on the inside bc it is the same dark colored wood as the sides and non silver parts. This would make it more realistic as a real fridge is white on the inside for example. I also wish there was a bit more free counter space for her to "cut" fruit or what not.The little counter space is next to the sink and is not too big. Also, the burners are not fixed to the counter so my baby kept taking them out so I glued them in so they are no longer removable.
I tried to order this on Amazon but it was difficult to find a seller that would ship to HI at all. I finally found one with a shipping fee that wasnt the same or more than the kitchen itself but Amazon sent me an email a week after I placed the order to tell me that the seller couldn't ship to HI after all. I was very annoyed that it took so long after I ordered it for Amazon to cancel the order. However I found this kitchen for a much lower price at W****rt and although the shipping was higher the total came out to be about the same, and the kitchen also came with a 125 piece food set which I was able to return at my local Walmart store and get part of my money back.
All in all we are happy with the kitchen! Assembly was arduous but definitely doable!

title: Tips for putting it together (it's worth it in the end).
text:
We just put this together last weekend and only gave it to our daughter for her 2 year birthday yesterday, so my feedback is based more on building it than on its longevity. Yes, it took my husband and I about 3.5 hours to build it. 3.5 hours and we used an electric drill with an allen wrench drill bit. So, if you don't have anything electric working for you, I can imagine it taking much longer. There are a million pieces to this thing: it can be overwhelming.

Tip 1: Don't start opening the hardware when you see it. Enter through the back as you go from step to step.
Tip 2: Some hardware has brown tips because the they will be up against the espresso wood. Some are merely silver because they will never be seen. The instructions do NOT specify when to use which. If this matters to you, you should be aware of it and take note of where the screws are going: if inside something like the refrigerator or stove, use the silver. If outside, use the brown.
Tip 3: Again, I highly recommend an electric drill and an allen wrench drill bit.
Tip 4: Divide up the work over two days or so if you're working with a partner so you don't kill each other.
Tip 5: Work with a partner. I can't imagine trying to do this alone. There are some parts where you literally need one person to hold something while the other drills/screws, etc.
Tip 6: Do NOT be tempted to do steps before you reach them in the directions. As flawed as I feel some of the directions are, doing the aforementioned will only add time to this already extensive project.
Tip 7: Read the directions beforehand. Get an idea of where you're headed, what's going together first, etc. It helped me visualize the process as we went along and therefore understand the directions better.

The result? She loves it. It's the longest stretch of independent play we've witnessed thus far. It looks real---just like our kitchen. She immediately set to putting a sponge under the faucet and cleaning her countertops. It was worth it.

title: Frustrating to build, lower/medium fit and finish.  Blahh.  Wouldn't buy again.
text:
[[VIDEOID:857fd5bf81c37fc1e96ae05f020f8b5c]] The first problem I have is the poor quality of 5-10 of my pieces. Big abrasions on the finish, cracked wood. 2 screws that are stripped right from the factory. 1 nut that is flat out just not machined well so it ruined another screw leaving me with 3 messed up screws.
Wood with the holes not drilled out deep enough or with pieces of scrap still stuck in the hole. I had to pocket knife some out to make pieces fit.
A few pieces are clearly scratched and damaged and it still was packed in the box. The shipment didn't cause the damage, The box was perfect. The abrasions and dents look bad but for a 2yr old to play with I wasn't about to pack up and ship back a huge box and cause myself a huge headache. I don't want to lug that huge box back to FedEx to return so I suck it up and know better for next time.
The build time is 3-4 hours for the average person. DO NOT use a drill, I have a drill on lowest settings and still had issues with it breaking the wood I'm careful about it and it still blew out holes that I ended up gluing together.
Keep that price in mind when you spend $129 bucks, You'll spend five times that in frustration and time to build it. I've done entire homes of Ikea furniture, this is definitely a step down from ikea build quality and finish. I'm not happy with it at all but for my 2yr old, he'll be happy with it. Ultimately it's a cheap thrill for the kid and I expect it to hold up a year or two and I'll junk it and he'll be on to the next thing.

If you can afford the more expensive stuff, get it. If not this should cut it if you are careful and get one that isn't all beat to hell like I did.

title: Pretty good for kids to have fun with.
text:
The kitchen has all the major appliances for imaginative play~fridge/freezer, microwave, oven, stove, sink, and dishwasher. However, the wireless phone and holder is a bit dated, haha! The pegs to hang mugs is a nice touch. The paper towel holder to the right of the dishwasher is functional. The espresso color is tasteful for the parents that don't want their kids' toy colors (i.e. loud child colors) to overwhelm their living space. This would not be much an issue if it lives in a child's room but for us, this lives in our living room.

When buying this, I suggest you get some other kitchen toys like pots/pans/utensils/play food items, etc.

Assembly instructions are pretty clear. Is it perfect? No, but good enough. Some plastic parts strip out easily; this happened to me when tightening a screw with my driver on the "ice maker" attached to the "fridge door". I fixed it by simply epoxying the ice maker to the door. My advice would be to use manual screw driver to tighten screws to avoid stripping out plastic parts. It took me a good 3 hours (including fixing broken parts) to put this together and I consider myself "experienced/handy". If you are not the handy type, plan on maybe 3.5-4 hrs. And, it's heavy enough that it's a good idea to ask somebody for help if you need to move it. It's not that heavy but it's bulky and becomes awkward to handle with just one person--no point in tweaking your back while doing this...

I took a star off because the plastic parts can be made better, or at least the instructions should warn you against using a power driver to avoid stripping the parts.

title: Really glad this is the kitchen we chose.
text:
Wow! I'm sure a lot of reviews have been written about this product, but here's ourt two cents: It's really great, lots of "functions"‚Äî phone, stove, microwave, etc. The stove knobs have a great feel and make a wonderfully "clicking" sound as you turn them. It's also much more compact than you might imagine. We assumed we'd have to store it in the garage or something, but it's very compact and fits in the girl's room wonderfully. They LOVE it.

The downside might be construction. Assembly took several hours and all the parts don't always match up perfectly. Also, if you tighten something down after say, step 22, by the time you reach step 45 you may find you piece doesn't fit right and you're going to have to lossen that stuff from back at step 22, insert your new piece and re-tighten. The pictures in the instructions can be vague as well. There's not any sort of "make sure that panel faces this direction". You're going to need to figure that out for yourself. Moreover, the package of hardware is equally murky. There are for example, "x" amount of "C" screws, however, some have brown heads, some have silver. There's not a distinction like screw "C-b" to signify "brown", they're all just labeled "C" and the instructions don't mention which you should use at any given point, so be sure you ration your screws appropriately otherwise at the end you'll be out of brown headed "C" screws and have too many silver headed "C" screws and if you want all the pieces to match, you'll need to go back and take something apart to get yourself another brown headed screw.

So, great product that the kids love, but the instructions and labeling could use work. 5 stars for the product 3 stars for the instructions. Lastly, as long as there are two adults, it can easily be constructed in the garage and moved then moved to your room of choice.

title: This play kitchen is beautiful!
text:
I just purchased and built this for my son. He loves it and his older brothers liked it as well. Now be prepared, you will open the huge heavy box and think "What have I gotten my self into.", but the end result will be completely worth it. There are as mentioned in other reviews only picture instructions. They aren't too difficult to follow once you get the hang of it. Simply make sure you have everything facing the way the directions show and you'll be fine. Eventually you get the hang of the instructions and figuring them out is easy. This is easiest to assemble as a two man team but I managed to build it alone while my husband was at work. I'd say without having to stop it would take between 2 to 3 hours. It took me longer because I had the kids bugging while I was trying to work on it.
Tip: Do not use a power drill use a screw driver because the screws strip easily and do not over tightened. There are a million screws so even if one is a little loose the kitchen will still be super sturdy.
There are multiples of the same type of hardware but some of them have different finished heads. For example some have brown painted heads so the blend into the wood. So just keep an eye out on where the piece will go because the instructions don't specify this and they aren't even marked differently on the hardware box. So you'd use a brown finished screw and bolt if you are placing the piece inside the fridge or icebox and if the piece is going, say inside the oven or being screwed into the back, you'd just use an unfinished screw and bolt. You will use all the hardware except for the pack that says extra because well that's extra.
The only negative comment I have is that two or the stove top coils came with damaged prongs, one was broken completely and the other was almost broken off. Each one comes with 3 prongs to screw in so it wasn't a big deal I just put the damaged ones in the back.
I'm not going to lie, this was a pain in the rear to put together just because it's so much to assemble but like I said before it will be very worth it. I expect it to last for many years.

title: Build quality review
text:
I am not going to try to offer an opinion on how much kids will enjoy this thing because that is not my area of expertise. This review is about build quality and time to build. On those subjects I have much experience. The good:
‚Ä¢ All the parts were there and the hardware is neatly packaged and decent quality
‚Ä¢ Pieces are well made. They are very and flat square and free of rough edges.
‚Ä¢ Plastic parts are of decent quality
‚Ä¢ Finish is good.
The not so good:
‚Ä¢ Parts are not packaged in the order they will be used leading to some searching.
‚Ä¢ Instructions are all visual and good enough but could be clearer
‚Ä¢ Packaging protects the parts but is really messy static charged Styrofoam.
‚Ä¢ Build time is long. If you get this done in under five hours and get it right you are pretty good.
‚Ä¢ You really should have a good electric screw driver or drill with a clutch to assemble this.
When my wife told me she bought this for our grandson I took a look at some reviews and the first thing that jumped out at me was the amount of time it took to build. I didn‚Äôt really feel too good about dumping a 5 or 6 hour job on my son in law so I put it together yesterday afternoon. Being retired makes so many things possible.
When you start make sure you have some space for this project. I used the space in our garage where I usually park my car. That is enough. We laid out all the panels based on their numbers in 4 stacks. 0 to to 10, 10 to 20, 20 to 30 etc. This will definitely save you some time. Keep all the plastic parts handy.
There are points in the process where it is a good idea to be using something like a work mate table for clamping or a second set of hands to hold stuff while screws, nuts, bolts and parts are assembled. Follow all the instructions and eventually it all comes together. Don‚Äôt try to pull this off on Christmas Eve after your kids have gone to bed. It would be a long night. All in all not a bad project but rather long. My wife thinks it‚Äôs great and will be a big hit so it‚Äôs all good

title: Well made Kitchen with lots of Extra features
text:
We spent a lot of time looking at different wooden (not plastic) kitchens for our 3 year old son. We chose this one because it had all the features we wanted (the little extra details such as the chalk board, ice cube dispenser on the fridge, dishwasher, paper towel holder and oven and phone as well as the main kitchen features like the fridge, freezer, shelf above, sink and oven). It was in the medium size range, not too small and not one of the corner units that we just didn't have room for. We are so glad we got this one!
Let me start by saying, like most other people that reviewed this product, it does take a long time to put together. My husband used to put items like this together for JCPenney and it took him 3 hours over 2 days. There were a ton of different components and pieces. Once its put together, though, it looks fantastic and has lots of little details that make it look really cute.
We brought this out as his last present at his birthday party and all 6 same age kids descended on it with fervor. As most 3-5 year olds are, they are pretty rough and wanted to explore ever inch of it- and it held up like a champ. The doors open and closed smoothly and have a little latch on the inside and another neat feature is inside the oven and washing machine the shelves slide out and in.
It got to us really quickly but was pretty heavy so I had the UPS guy wheel it into the house...lol.
I recommend this kitchen to any budding chef or child who likes "helping." Its a great product and we are so glad we got it.

Much more realistic. Assembly was extremely time consuming. I have put together countless pieces of furniture and toys and this toy took longer than my 6 yr olds bunk bed with trundle. Approximately 4-5 hrs by myself. The pieces are labeled well and instructions are step by step but I did have some trouble with a couple pieces of hardware being stripped out before use. Not a huge problem but adds to the time. Overall I think this is a nice toy. It came with 30 pieces of food and i got a free set of pots and pans that sweetened the deal. title: Love it!
text:
Glad that we selected this kitchen! I was hesitant at first because of the reviews in which people said that assembly was a nightmare and nothing worked... This wasn't our experience AT ALL.

After our son went to bed, hubby hauled the box (heavy, but not 100 lbs as stated in a negative review) to an open area with good lighting so that we could account for and organize everything for assembly.

It's a good idea to review the instructions completely and catalogue each piece before beginning assembly. I'd also recommend not waiting until the day before to begin assembly. We ordered and received this kitchen in advance and put it together to allow time for any possible corrections.

Yes, there are a lot of screws and boards, but that's to be expected -- otherwise, you'd 1) complain that it needs additional support/screws... or 2) complain that the box is too big if it were partially assembled.
If the screws didn't align for us, it was because we had the piece turned the wrong way (gotta pay attention to the pictures in the instructions).
End result: everything aligned just fine.
And, yes, some of the screws have different finishes. The instructions didn't point that out, but...the brown-head screws go on the brown board/pieces; the white screw-heads goes on the white board; and the silver-head screws go on the undersides/parts not visible.

It took us several hours (we took our time, chatted, snacked, ...), but our patience and hard work paid off.

It looks great and seems extremely durable. I'm excited -- can't wait for our son to see and play with it!

Some may prefer a more "childlike" kitchen, but this is one that I hope will grow with our son. The "stainless" finish is nice, and the espresso finish matches the KidKraft table and chairs that we purchased.

I thought that I read that this comes with a baking pan, but it doesn't. No big deal; I'll just grab one separately.

At this point, I have no complaints and would definitely recommend this kitchen.

title: *DO NOT WAIT TO ASSEMBLE* Side note: This kitchen is amazing!
text:
I'm going to keep this short and sweet:

1) This kitchen is AWESOME. Well worth the money. You're basically robbing them, in my opinion.
2.) You WILL, without a doubt, need absolutely no less than 4 hours to put this together. I assumed people were exaggerating when they said it took them 6 hours to assemble it.. they were not. My husband assembled most of it on his own, with the exception of a few parts in which it was helpful to have a second person hold something. It took him 5 hours with the exception of about a 15 minute break.
3.) If at all possible, assemble this is a large space. We put ours together on our driveway while our daughter was at school. (Tip* Lay old blankets down to protect the surfaces of each piece) Assembling in a smaller space, or trying to do so quietly (think Christmas Eve), would definitely length the time it takes to put together.
4.) Don't expect great directions. They get the job done but aren't exceptionally helpful either.
5.) One strong person can carry this and without much of a hassle maneuver a staircase, hallway, or door. Two people could definitely do it!
*FOR THE LOVE OF GOD TO NOT WAIT UNTIL CHRISTMAS EVE TO ASSEMBLE THIS!

title: Fun toy with significant assembly
text:
This kitchen has a lot of parts to put together, but once finished has provided hours of entertainment for our toddler (in about 15 minute intervals). The shelves slide out which can be a pro if your child likes to "hide" inside the dishwasher section but can be a pain when they migrate to other rooms and get lost. The material isn't the highest quality, but there are a ton of knobs and doors that are still working well after a couple months. Full size round pans stolen from my kitchen cabinets also fit in the oven which is very exciting for my child.
The first kitchen we received was damaged in shipping and Amazon sent us a replacement immediately, which was helpful, and we managed to get all 35+ parts back in the box without too much trouble. Two people putting it together took us an hour once we'd laid out all the parts on the floor.

title: beautiful, and has all the useful features our kitchen ...
text:
This kitchen set is modern, beautiful, and has all the useful features our kitchen has.

I, the mom, assembled it all by myself in total of 5 hrs. Yes, that is a lot of time... There are a lot of pieces and parts! It's a doable project and I'm not handy at all!

The kitchen is sturdy and makes sense. Though I wish there was battery operated sounds for the microwave and sink and other parts, that is asking for too much :).
The kitchen is hot in our house when we have my 2.5yo friends over. It's amazing how much more imaginative these kids get when they can role play with tangible objects.

We play in this kitchen every day.
These were all the pros.

Now for the cons:
Wish it came with some pretend play food, pots/pans. We had to buy everything separately which added more $$$! We found out Walmart is the only store that sells this kitchen with pretend food! O well, we still love the kitchen, and so does my son!

They are kind of wobbly. The rest of the kitchen is pretty sturdy and guests are always impressed by how realistic it looks. I bought it during a sale and I'm glad I didn't pay retail cost as I don't feel it's worth that much.

title: A wonderful kitchen. It does take between 3 and 4 ...

title: Solid 'board' pieces, cheap assembly hardware and plastic pieces
text:
The screw hole posts on the plastic pieces shear off too easy when screwing on. The first one was probably on me, but I was careful after that and still sheared two more. I think I'd glue them instead if I had to do it again.
Also, the furniture cam lock and nuts are cheap (they don't lock in quite right). They loosened and came out after a week, and my kid brought it to me and asked what it was. I left them out after that as I didn't want my kid swallowing and choking on them. Sturdy enough without it though.
Not bad for the price, though I'd spend more and get something better if I had to choose again.

title: Nice but it is the bane of my existence- Updated
text:
I bought this for my daughter because make believe play is really important for development. The details are really cool in this kitchen. The MDF is veneered to look like real wood and the counter top is painted with silver splashes to look like granite or quartz. However nice this kitchen is it gets tainted by the awful task of putting it together. It isn't trying to find the nuts, bolts, and screws (they are all packaged nicely and labeled with a cardboard back that can be opened by compartment). It isn't figuring out which piece is which (all the pieces are labeled with numbers on stickers). It isn't even the picture instructions (if you're like me and have put together more ikea furniture than you care to say then you're fluent in picture). It's just that there is so many pieces and so much detail that makes it difficult. I had to put it together myself because my husband decided to go hunting and I had to take a lot of breaks because my back would seize up but I think it took 3 hours of work to put together by myself. Overall it's a nice product but it got 4 stars because you basically have to be a structural engineer to put it together.

UPDATE: It is now 2018 and has been almost 4 years since I have purchased and put this item together. I am updating it to 5 stars cause even though t was a pain to put it together it is still standing! My daughter actually doesn't want it anymore, but it is still in really good shape to sell to someone else. For the 3 hours that it took to put together it really was worth it.

title: Really cute, assembly instructions could use some work.
text:
Fully assembled, this is actually really cute, and my son loves it. I thought the price was pretty reasonable considering its size, and the fact that it seems like it will be fairly durable. The box is 70 lbs., and the packing looked a little rough when it arrived, but the foam inside the box seems to have absorbed any damage, as no parts were noticeably damaged.

That said, the assembly instructions that came with mine were pretty wonky. The parts are numbered, but the part numbers don't have any relationship to the order they're used in the assembly instructions. The first step involves attaching part 40 to part 6. The set comes with some screws which are identical but for the color, but the instructions don't specify where to use espresso screws vs. silver screws. When you're initially assembling the kitchen, it isn't always apparent which side of a panel will be the inside or outside, so you'll likely use some espresso screws in the wrong places, and end up with silver screws where espresso screws should have been used. They also use letters to label the fasteners, but the fasteners aren't laid our on the panel in alphabetical order, so if you're looking for "screw D" it might be in the middle of the panel. Those are minor issues, but fixing those issues wouldn't take much effort on KidKraft's part either.

The plastic ice dispenser cracked as I screwed in two of the screws (the plastic part that you screw into broke off). The two remaining screws seem to hold it together well enough, so I just used a bit of glue to provide some additional support. This solution seems solid enough.

It took me 2-2.5 hours to assemble. A small electric screwdriver will save you a ton of time assembling this, but you'll need to take care to avoid over-tightening the screws.

title: Faucet may get ripped off - but otherwise this is a huge huge hit.
text:
My son loves this set. The only down-side is that he and his cousin (both under the age of 2, actually it was my son's first birthday) took like 10 minutes to rip off the faucet. We thought about reattaching it but decided to just leave it off since it would likely get pulled off again.

As for assembly, my husband and I were shocked by the number of pieces and hardware. I think there were over 150 bolts, washers, etc. so this is how we spent our Christmas: building this set.

Still, we wanted a masculine looking kitchen set with modern elements to match out own kitchen and this one takes the cake. I looked at a lot of kitchen sets before deciding on this one. I love that it's gender neutral because for play dates neither the boys or girls can claim it's too boy or girl like. Also, when we go to resell the kitchen, I bet people will really like it.

We set up the kitchen in our kitchen and my son often "cooks" while I cook. He makes running water noises, he talks on the phone, he puts things in the microwave, he pulls things out of the refrig. Also, if you are like us and lacking space after your kid is born, this is the set for you. We store our cereals on the top of the kitchen and our son can't reach them. Plus we store cans of corn and such in the refrig since our son loves to play with cans, and it offers a lot of extra storage.

Our cleaners also store our son's toys in this unit. It can fit a lot, lot lot in the set. Speaking of which, be sure to measure before you buy this set. It fits perfect for us (depth is quite narrow!), but we did measure before hand because the width is huge. In a good way.

title: Adorable and durable play kitchen
text:
We absolutely love this play kitchen! The details are exceptional and my daughter loves that it looks "just like mommy's." The multiple cupboards allow for a lot of imaginary play and provide many storage options. We bought this for our daughter's first birthday and she was able to reach the bottom 3 no problem which was plenty sufficient. With time she became tall enough to reach the freezer and microwave as well. At the age of 3 she doesn't seem too big for it and actually has room to grow, unlike many other play kitchens. Additionally, after 2 solid years with almost daily use it still looks almost brand new and we haven't had any issues. It has withstood tugging and pulling and climbing.

The only negative is it is a beast to put together. There are lots of pieces and lots of directions that need to be followed in specific order. So give yourself plenty of time and pour yourself a drink before starting. But in the end it's totally worth it!

title: "KidKraft Prank Your Assembler" toy is what I call it.
text:
If you want to keep your marriage/bf/etc, buy something else. It is however an excellent gag gift for with your husband
Sadly my wife's 5 star item turns into my 1 star nightmare.
All these 4 to 5 star ratings must have been people who didn't have to go through assembly.

You should plan on 30-45 mins of cataloging the items in your garage/outdoors(they are all rectangles) and another 2 hrs and 40 mins of straight assembly!!!!

Comes in an Ikea style flat shipping box, contains 45 Pieces and 21 nuts and bolts. Don't worry it gets worse. Screw type C and bolt type A had multiple finishes. How about labeling them C1/C2/C3 and A1/A2 instead of just C and A. I had to go to page 12 (of 14) the instruction booklet to figure out if I should use the brown,metal, or the white finish for step 2 and 3..... Furthermore, due to the weight of the package fully expect the foam to be shredded upon delivery. SO OPEN IN YOUR GARAGE/OUTSIDE. If you open the package in your house, you better expect a full styrofoam snow shower in your house.

As for the "sturdy structure that was designed by passionate engineers" comment.... They must be "engineers", without kids, and never once tried to assemble their own product. The sturdy design is obviously geared toward light adult use. There is no way a good Engineer would have put screws into the side of MDF(maybe paper) pieces without metal supports and expect it to last, specially on door clips. That is just asking for it to break when used by 3 y/o. The instructions followed the 80/20 rule(80% done using only 20% of effort).... Not very well thought out... It is obvious that this product was never assembled by KIDKRAFT's engineers or they would have updated the instructions in frustrations. Finally they must have had no kid because there is no way adults with a young kid has 3+ hours to spare for the assembly of a toy.

Like I said if you want to have huge fight/gag gift/start a divorce, this is the toy to get. Nothing is more aggravating than a toy with bad instructions.

title: Wonderful kitchen set! - UPDATED 04/08/2014
text:
I LOVE this kitchen set. It goes well with our decor and it's really nice looking. The only down side to this set is that it's a pain in the butt to put together. It really took a few hours to put this together and came with SO MANY SCREWS! But I still think it was worth all the time and effort to put it together. My toddler loves this toy and I can see this getting many many hours of use over the years to come.

** UPDATE AS OF 11/20/2013 ** There is a "ice maker" that is part of the fridge that CONSTANTLY comes loose. As far as I can tell, there is no way to secure it to the fridge door. It's a plastic part that has 4 dowels in the back that pops into 4 holes on the fridge. There are no screws, no nothing to secure it other than the dowels in the holes. My 17 month old bangs the fridge door and inevitably, the ice maker part falls out. It's not a terrible issue and I still love the kitchen (as does my toddler) so I'm not about to knock off stars for it since crazy glue should be able to resolve the issue ... but it's worth mentioning.

** UPDATE AS OF 4/8/2014 ** This kitchen is taller and bigger than the "vintage style" kidkraft kitchen. I mention this because my kid is tall, but she has to tippy toe to open the microwave door on the top. At her friends house, she can open the microwave quite easily. So if you have a particularly tall child, or would like longer use out of your toy kitchen, this is the one to purchase since it's TALLER AND BIGGER than the other ones by KidKraft. Worth mentioning if it helps other parents make a decision on one or the other.

Neither child (1 1/2 yr old twins) has stopped playing with it since receiving it Christmas day. FYI-the towel bar and shelving in the oven and dishwasher are removable/not secured so it may be an issue for younger children.

The stove knobs click when turned. The faucet handle moves. It does come with anchors to secure the entire structure.

Note: I was concerned when the item arrived via FexEx. The box was smashed and torn in several places. Thankfully none of the pieces were scratched.

Note: My husband thought it only would take about an hour to put together, but it took much longer. There were many packages of screws, but all pieces were numbered.

Note: I could not find KidKraft cooking utensils at the time. I ordered the Ikea pots/pans/utensils. They do not fit on the hanging pegs. I'm not sure if any others would.

title: Look No Further! Great Kitchen!
text: This kitchen is the best! When we order larger/more expensive items for the kids, we always do our research before settling on one. It's very sturdy & easy to assemble but VERY time consuming. The piece that clicked the washer shut had broken during assembly but it still closes so it's really not an issue for us. The only two things I don't like are: 1) The sink just sits in there. We'll probably end up glueing it ourselves. 2) The towel rod also just sits there so the kids can take it out easily. It makes me a little uneasy that the kids (especially my youngest) could grab it & run around with a rod but we'll manage. I do wish the washer/oven doors opened like real ones would BUT it's not a problem obviously. My kids absolutely love this new kitchen & they've been playing with it nonstop. It seems like it'll last a long time, well worth the money spent. Might have to get the matching washer/dryer set!

title: It is a Head Ache to Assemble (but they all are)
text: Durability is questionable, at best, for this unit.  The countertop had already flaked off a large chunk before my 2 YO daughter even got a chance to use it.  The hinges and doors have held up so far, though, after nearly 3 months of use.  My biggest warning is that assembly will take a while for this unit.  Figure on four hours to construct with just one person (of better than average skill).  Just don't put it off until Christmas Eve, or just before a Birthday Party, and think you can assemble this tedious thing by yourself in a few minutes.  On the upside, the size fits well in the corner of a room without getting in the way, and aesthetically looks much better than most of the other pink & purple monstrosities.  My daughter wants her kitchen to be just like the adult kitchen anyway, so she wouldn't want a pink powder puff version.

title: Must buy for your toddler!
text:
I have been looking for a play kitchen for my 2 year old son. He loves helping with dishes, playing in the sink, and putting groceries away. After reading numerous reviews I finally decided on this particular one. I wanted one that didn't look cheap or plastic. I wanted it to be sturdy and go well with his ever-changing room themes and decor. I was super anxious for it to arrive and to put it together. I read some reviews about damaged parts and it taking forever to put together so I didnt want to waste any time once it got here.

The first package I got there was a deep gash in the little ice machine part. I emailed them and they sent a replacement. Customer service was excellent and they were very prompt. ***they cannot ship you just one replacement part, they have to ship you the entire kitchen set over again and you're responsible for sending back one set or you WILL be charged for two ****

Other then that all the other parts had no big issues. Some minor scratches that's all. Everything was labeled with stickers which made it super simple. It took my husband and I about 1 and a half hours to assemble this. Not as bad as I was expecting so that was a huge plus. Once it got put together it looked really nice and was super stable.

Pros:
-modern look
-sturdy
-durable
-burners click when you turn them
-lots of room inside

Cons:
-number buttons are just painted on, they don't make noise
-plastic in the stove door looks flimsy but we will see how long it lasts
-would be cool if it had a light built in above sink

So I really don't have anything bad to say about it. I will purchase more kid kraft products in the future. I have already bought the laundry set to go with this and they look great together. If you have any questions or are curious about purchasing this ask and I willove be glad to help!

title: Beautiful Kitchen, Difficult Assembly
text: Bought this for my son who is 1&1/2. When we finally got it all together, it kept him busy for hours!! It's a beautiful wood kitchen, very heavy and sturdy. Everything arrived in perfect condition. I'd say the biggest downfall was the assembly of this thing. It took quite a bit of time. (Even with 3 adults trying to put it together). The directions are just pictures and the hardest part is that some of the same screws are silver while others are brown and it doesn't tell you which one to use, so you have to figure out if the piece you're working on will be going on the inside (silver screws) or outside (brown screws) of the kitchen. You also have to figure out the fronts and backs of all the pieces because it doesn't clarify that in the directions either. And the only thing I didn't really like about the kitchen itself was the shelving on the inside of the oven and dishwasher, I wish it wasn't so easily removable because my son continues to take them out. But besides all that, once we got it together, it was definitely worth it in the end. And I'm hoping this lasts for many years.

text:

Also, we got the cell phone/iphone "look alike" phone as opposed to the big wall phone others have mentioned they received. Wish the phone had a cord to it so that it doesn't get brought from room to room- but my son loves talking on it!
The piece is solid, and just so adorable. I've attached pictures to show kitchen fully built. We got IKEA pots and pans that fit perfectly; M&D felt sandwich making set, M&D wooden fridge and M&D pantry set, M&D Food cutting set, M&d Grocery can set, M&D playtime veggie set, M&D Christmas cookie set, Le Toy Van Wooden Pops, Learning Resources Dish Set, and PBS Sandwich stacker. All of those items fit into the kitchen no problem. Also, I have kept old M&D wooden holders from other toys and have used them to hold items in the kitchen to keep it a bit more organized. We ended up getting the M&D coffee maker, as well as the Kidkraft Espresso Toaster later as a gift (Both items not pictured) and both of the items fit great on the small counter, and the shelf above the sink. I also got a little tin bucket from the Target $1 section to hang on the knobs for holding all the big spoons and spatulas. Wishing the spoons could have hung there, but the knobs are so big! So happy with purchase, our child loves it- especially the microwave, and we are having a blast cooking :) Highly recommend this kitchen!

title: Great Kitchen that looks amazing in person!
text: I purchased this for a gift for my daughter who will be turning 5.  The height is great, I would say  the age range would be from 3 years to older, but it's not too bulky or large to fit nicely in a playroom, kitchen etc . . . you have to admit, it looks beautiful! First, I will start with the packaging, the box is very heavy and I noticed the reviews on this product show the process of putting this kitchen together is time consuming.  It took me around 3 hours, I chose to do this over a period of 2 days so it really didn't seem that bad - if you plan on it, it will be less stressful.  The instructions are very well put together, besides having a picture diagram for each piece there is also a screw/tool set that is numbered accordingly (pictured below) it looks overwhelming at first but trust me, it is very easy.  Now, the only thing I would say you need to know that is not written in the instructions is the "A" pieces and the "C" Screws have two different options.  One is the Brown Colored heads which will go on the pieces that will be visible and the Silver Colored heads will be the ones that go on the inside pieces.  Also, the middle wood panel has the sliding pieces that will go on both sides.  In the instructions it looks like it will only go on one side, but it should be on both as this will hold the "Cutting Board" and "Shelf" (under the Sink/Stove.)  Once you put this together, you will notice the nice details and finish. The board pieces are painted wood, so it does not have the cheap paneling that may wear off in time, for this reason I am confident this should stay looking great for a long time.  This does not come with accessories but it does come with the phone, chalkboard, cutting board, shelving and the knobs to hang cookware.  I am very excited for my daughter to use and I love that it looks great and is not tacky or bulky to have anywhere in the house!

title: Very nicely built and perfect for your budding chef.
text:
This is a really cool design. It's a bear to assemble, though, as it took me 3 hours and i actually build furniture, cabinetry and all things wood and metal. There are a LOT of pieces and this sucker is heavy. Shipping weight is 78 lbs and the packaging is less than exciting.
Our first delivery of this item arrived in pieces. It seems the Dallas UPS center employs an 800 lb gorilla with a PCP habit and bad attitude to handle their large packages. I've had more deliveries destroyed here with UPS than ever in my history - and I ran a shipping and receiving dept. for 3 years. The Dallas office of UPS can destroy ANYTHING - so this item was a piece of cake for them.
When I received the totally destroyed product, I contacted the seller and they were most apologetic, offering to FedEx a replacement. Unfortunately, this product is too heavy for FedEx, so the replacement arrived via UPS and - miraculously - arrived in one piece!
Assembly:
Give yourself some space to work on (carpeted so you don't scratch the pieces while assembling them) and allocate several hours to the task.
There are different colors of 2 different screws.

The "C" screws come in shiny metal, wood colored - and there is one white one. The directions do not make a distinction between these.
The screws with the wood colored heads go against the wood colored surfaces (most of the exterior.
The silver screws go against metal or the interior when they will not be seen.
The one white capped "C" screw goes on the "telephone" panel on the right side of the panel to the left of the microwave.

The A / E combination screw / embedded nut assemblies come in 2 colors as well - and there is one shiny metal set of a different letter that is just a little longer. These go into the vertical metal pipe that hold the right end of the shelf / microwave assembly.
Again, the wood colored screw heads go against the wood finish and the silver ones go where you won't see them (on the back and inside)

You don't need any additional tools other than a phillips head screwdriver to assemble this unit. Just take your time and I found a rolling short shop stool to be the most comfortable way to do the assembly. Otherwise you'll spend a lot of time on your knees.

title: Pretty nice product
text: This thing looks great. Pretty good detail. Took me about 2 hours to assemble. Im a 23 year old father who is great with his hands and very fast on average. My son is going to absolutely love this. It's a tad bigger than expected which is great. Product arrive with pretty extensive damage to the box. However, I work in a warehouse and am aware of how often things like this occur and actually don't damage the item inside the box. Plus this thing came with great inner styrofoam packaging. I assume the damage to the box had something to do with the time of the year the item was shipped as UPS and FedEx are extremely busy right now due to Christmas. It was a little more difficult to put together than I would have liked and expected for something of this nature. The instruction manual pictures are rather small. I struggled to see several parts of the assembly process and couldn't imagine how someone slightly older with lower performing eyesight would see these. I took a vision test last year and have perfect vision.  Part numbers Q and R I believe could use a different design. I did away with them all together. I got frustrated with them because logically they made no sense to me. I've used so many different types of hardware and I have never seen anything like this. I am a somewhat experienced wood worker so I took a taper bit to hide the screw heads and boared out some holes close to where the Q and R support peices were suppose to go and just zipped in some small 1" screws to hold the middle and right side of the counter top down. Had I not ran in to this issue with the design of these hardware pieces and the length of time it took me to put this together I would have given this 5 stars. Annoying to put together, but after this thing is put together it is worth it. Id do it again for my son!

title: Nice set for the money.

title: Lots of assembly required
text:
I just finished putting this kitchen together for my daughter's Christmas present. So far it appears to be a sturdy, well made kitchen. We will see how it stands up to a toddler. I just wanted to comment and leave some advice for assembly. This comes in a box with zero parts pre-assembled.

DO NOT wait until the night before to start putting it together. I would say that I spent 4 to 5 hours working on it.

There is a package that comes with all of the screws and things for assembly. There are multiple locations of the same parts, some are brown and some are silver. I didn't pay attention at first and used some of the brown screws on the inside of the kitchen, which would have left silver screws on the outside on brown wood. Some people may not care, but my OCD compelled me to fix my error.

Overall, the instructions are fairly clear. On step 15, make sure that piece #1 has the slat for the back veneer facing down. That's the only place that I had trouble.

Good luck!!

title: Nice for the price
text:
Scored a deal on this at $89.99 about 10 days before Christmas so it is likely worth watching the price if you are considering. Not sure I would have went with this item had it remained around $120 price point as it does not come with any accessories besides the toy cell phone.

Was pleasantly surprised it was intact upon arrival as one corner of the box was pretty crushed. Quality of the pieces was very good and went together smoothly in about 3hrs by myself. I was happy all the doors lined up and gaps around the edges were good except the microwave which was a little askew but still closes.

This has a lot of storage with a shelf in each lower cabinet and the fridge which seemed nice compared with some of the plastic units we were also considering.

title: Not the same as advertised image. Quality issues.
text:
Yes, it‚Äôs cute. However, the manufacturer has obviously cut some corners at the expense of the consumer. My biggest issue is that the utensil hangers that were supposed to be part of the backsplash behind the oven/sink were missing. This was clearly intentional since the portion of the backsplash meant to attach them to was also missing (so backsplash overall was downsized considerably versus advertised image). Also, the chalk board in the picture has a nice stainless colored raised frame around it, but what I received was just a ‚Äúframed‚Äù chalkboard sticker. It‚Äôs really cheap looking.

This kitchen was expensive, and I expected to receive exactly what was in the advertised image. The backsplash/utensil hanger absence bugged me most, as it really takes away from the overall look of the kitchen.

Final issue- even after several attempted adjustments, the door of the oven and under-sink cabinet do not hang right, and therefore, do not shut nicely. Better quality would have been nice....

Would not purchase again, especially at this price.

title: Love it!

title: Took 6 hours and a Masters of Engineering degree to assemble... literally
text: It hurts me to write this.  I was SO excited to get this kitchen, and I'm still excited for my daughter (2.5 years) to enjoy it.  However, I have to warn potential buyers.  ONLY BUY THIS KITCHEN IF YOU HAVE 6 HOURS TO ASSEMBLE IT.  And no, that is not an exaggeration.  Not only does it come in a bazillion separate pieces, but many of the pieces are the wrongs size, with holes in the wrong places, or other bizarre problems.  For example, screws that are too short.  If I didn't have my brilliant and extremely handy engineer of a father-in-law (literally he is an engineer), I would have a useless pile of parts instead of a kitchen.  Even so, there was a point 4 hours deep into the assembly that I thought we were going to have to return it.  After 4 HOURS of time that would have been wasted!  OK fine, if they insist on sending in so many tiny pieces, but there is NO EXCUSE for pieces that don't actually fit together!  The number of mistakes was unbelievable.  So, buyer be warned.  On the positive side, it really does look great and seems sturdy... if you can ever actually get it put together.

title: Headache to put together, but very cute set
text: Ok, so if you have ever put together ikea furniture. That's basically what this is. Its ikea quality. It's a headache. This is a job for 2 people, not one. So plan on that. The directions don't tell you what to do first, it goes by vague pictures. But, too many times, I had to go back and redo or take apart. There is a huge pack of hardware that comes with extra hardware. Be prepared to use the extra hardware, as a lot of the bolts and screws strip easily. Have an extra L wrench on hand as well, the one they give you strips out. Also, plan on a few different sizes of screw heads. What really makes you mad, is that the bolts and screws are all different colors and don't match, so you have non matching pieces all over. And there isn't enough of the pretty ones to use on the outside, so you have to use the other ones. Nothing in this set is pre assembled,you literally put every piece on. If I would have had an extra hand, it would've been much easier. But since I didn't, it took me about 8 hrs of assembly while caring for the kids and what not. In the end, it's a cute set and not an eye sore to have in the house. We didnt buy the pots and pans. We already had play food and such, and that works just fine with it.

title: Assembly in 2 Hours- our tips
text:
Challenged by previous reviews, we wanted to complete the assembly as quick as possible. My husband spent about 15 minutes "staging" everything. Most of the time I was attaching pieces and screws as he prepped the next step. It helped keep the process moving and we only had one small hiccup. A hole was a tad loose for the door stopper- so we used a dab of wood glue. We finished assembly in about an hour and 45 minutes- plus the staging time- right at two hours.

title: Amazing kitchen, but give yourself some serious build time!
text:
This kitchen is beautiful. It is sturdy. It has storage for days. My children adore it.

It IS a complicated build though. Not difficult, just A LOT to do. With my husband and I, on Christmas Eve, it took us 5 HOURS. Together.

We did not sleep that night, BUT we have no regrets on it because the end result is so enjoyed and SO STYLISH for a kid's play kitchen.

The colors model more of what an actual kitchen would be like, not crazy primary colors and chunky features (for safety I guess, but this is perfectly safe enough even for my nearly 2 year old to not hurt himself).

It has ample storage for all of their kitchen toys as well as a pair of potato head toys which my daughter really feels belong in the freezer compartment. The Mrs kinda gives me a start when I open it. Ha ha!

We are still in the honeymoon phase on durability, but if their other Christmas gifts are already showing signs of wear, this one is showing all the signs of standing the test of time.

My kids are nearly 5 and nearly 2, and both VERY tall, and this kitchen is just the right height for my 90th height percentile son and tall enough for daughter. Most kitchens we looked at have her bending down to play with most of the features offered, but here she is like an adult, bending for the oven, dishwasher, and the very bottom of the fridge.

Skip the plastic everything kitchens. Get this one and give yourself time to build it, and it will be treasured for a long time to come.

title: It's fine

title: Good quality, realistic
text: This is a fairly solid, attractive play kitchen. My 4 yo granddaughter loves it, and I did stock it with Melissa and Doug food and equipment. (She later asked me to take her home because, "My kitchen is waiting!) I like that this is realistic and even looks good in my son's living room. I'm not a fan of gaudy, bright colored plastic toys for role playing. Assembly was a challenge, but instructions had mostly clear, large pictures (no words). I am a long time DIY grandma who has helped build houses and repaired many things. It took me 5 hours total to assemble. I spent 2 hours assembling all of the handles, accessories, stove top, and shelf hardware. A lot of that time involved finding the correct parts and getting then out of the packaging. ***Alert- pay attention to the screws and bolts, as directions do not mention that some are brown to match the wood when visible, and others are chrome (they're all given the same letter/number key). Some of my time was wasted switching these around once I realized it. The main construction took three hours, and I had estimated one! Some of that was the hardware switching, but much was the counter top attachment- it would have been easier to attach all of the parts, such as the faucet, before attaching to the unit. The area around the sink had stubborn hardware that didn't want to stay tight, and I feel this is its most vulnerable spot for coming apart, especially since it is likely to be picked up at that edge.  I must have removed it and started over at least four times. The microwave shelf post on mine is not quite right in height, and the top shelf is not straight because of it- tried to sand down one end (hard plastic) which improved it a little. I may eventually try to fix it again. Another useful tip from the You Tube video is to use dish soap on the screws. This was very helpful when screwing into plastic parts. It's all hand tighten; power tools would be risky for damage.

title: Assembly is difficult but ultimately worth it
text: I bought this for my daughter's 2nd birthday and it looks just as nice in person as it does on-line.  What I wasn't 100% prepared for was how difficult it would be to put together.  Assembly took almost 6 hours so be prepared (unless you are a professional carpenter) you will likely need another person to help assemble, a lot of patience and an entire afternoon.  There are no written directions and no on-line videos (I've noticed a lot of toy manufacturers have started doing this and it is very helpful).  The pictures they provide in the instructions are not clear. I was also really disappointed that ours was missing some of the screws and some of the other parts were either not long enough or didn't fit properly.  A trip to the hardware store fixed that and was easier to spend a couple of bucks and get it done than calling the manufacturer and waiting on them to send replacement parts.  There were also some scratches and nics in the wood.  Nothing major enough that I would return it, most were not visable unless you are up close and after some serious play from a toddler similar imperfections are bound to pop up, so ultimately I would recommend this play kitchen and your kids will love it.

text:
My daughter and I bought this cute little kitchen for my granddaughter's 2nd birthday. We figured she should have her own little kitchen set, and we were right. Do we love it? Yes. Does she? Yes. Is it sturdy? Yes. Good quality? Yes. Easy to put together? For my daughter and I, yes. Price? Better than the rest.

title: POSITIVES AND NEGATIVES!
text:
I purchased this for my 18 month old grandaughter. I have some very Positives and some "sort of" Negatives.

Positive: This set has proven to be a true hit with her and I feel that she will be able to grow with it - the size is perfect, it looks incredible. She LOVES all of the nooks and crannies as well as the turning knobs and sink features. She loves to do the "ring ring" and answer the phone. She is still a little too small to reach the upper shelves but I feel that in a matter of months that will no longer be an issue.

Negative: When this was first shipped the packaging was DESTROYED. When we contacted Amazon we were referred to the dealer. While they did eventually ship us new parts, they wanted us to inventory everything and give them an itemized list of things that were damaged. Sounds easy, but there are hundreds of parts. We ended up listing something like 60 pieces that were damaged beyond using. They then shipped us a box with those pieces in it - two days later they shipped us another box with those 60 pieces in it. On Christmas Eve while trying to assemble it, we literally had multiple pieces of everything and the whole sorting process became very confusing. Once figured out though we are VERY happy with the set.

title: A bit of a project, but completely worthwhile when done!
text:
Smart stuff:
1. the "oven" and "dishwasher" open horizontally like cupboards - while this is less accurate, it solves the problem of kids standing on the doors that in other sets open downward, and instantly are broken.
2. The set feels really solid, it's probably nicer than my actual kitchen cupboards and feels like it will last for a long time. I figured that "backsplash" was cardboard like so many flimsy bookshelves I've put together, but nope, it's actually wood - way better.
3. The colors are neutral - this is good both for multi-gender families as well as more aesthetically pleasing when plopped in amongst my other furniture. It's not the giant plastic eyesore so many other sets are.

Not loving:
1. the door latches are a bit hard to maneuver for my 2 year old, despite her being VERY rough and physical, they are pretty stiff. Might loosen up over time, but some frustration when she can't open all the doors
2. Removable shelves in the two lower cabinets, not sure why but those shelves are the first thing she takes out. Wish they were just stationary, but this is a small gripe.
3. Putting it together took about 3 hours - it was definitely do-able, no individual task was that hard, I was able to do it myself with just the included materials + a power screwdriver, but I wasn't quite expecting that many steps. Was absolutely worth it though.

Overall:
We've had this put together for a few weeks now, and I love it. My just turned 2 year old is pretty tall for her age, but I can see this set lasting for years, and it works great for her now as well. It is streamlined enough to not be obnoxious, but still has all the bells and whistles (without anything that makes bell or whistle noises, YAY! The oven dials do click when turned, but there aren't any other sound effects, even the phone is just a block of wood. I find that refreshing after so many noisy flashing toys). The sink is her favorite part, and she yanks on the "spout" frequently but it is well made and surviving.
I like how sturdy it is - unlike the plastic, I'm not worried she will tip it over, fall through it, or rip out the screws. This piece is basically furniture. It has a LOT of storage, so clean up is easy - all the play food and dishes can be stored inside the refridgerator and dishwasher without being seen. I also like that it is fairly neutral - both gender neutral and just design neutral. It is a large toy, but doesn't overwhelm my space with loud colors or garish finishes. It actually "matches" the armoire next to it quite well :)

Highly recommended

title: Terrible To Assemble & Never Heard Back From Customer Service
text:
This was the worst thing we have ever purchased. It arrived damaged on five pieces, also missing two screws in the needed color. I emailed them twice and never heard back. I called them and they said they never received my emails and could I resend the pictures. This was after four days of having the box at our house and Christmas a few days away. We had no choice but to put it together. If we'd waited for new pieces ( that is assuming they would make right the damaged product they sent us) Christmas would have been long gone. To receive replacement parts, of damaged parts, would require disassembling the set. This whole thing was a nightmare.
It took over eight hours to put together. You have to unpack many pieces, lay them out and nothing goes in numerical order. You may need part 1 with part 39. There are I don't know how many screws.... We finally put them each by letter in individual Baggies and lettered them and it still took eight hours. A woman can not do this alone unless you are very strong. You still need two people in parts. Not a single written instruction in spite of all the steps. The screws are made out of a hard plastic and are almost impossible to screw in unless you are practically Superman, such cheap cheap quality. My husband and I approached this as a doctor and nurse. He put it together, I read the instructions and handed him the pieces. Shame on KidKraft for shipping out damaged pieces, making something so tedious to assemble and the poor quality of manufacturing.
A huge disappointment and frustration. Terrible customer service to not return my calls and emails and to manufacture poor goods.

She def uses her imagination as I got her some pots & pans (I bought Melissa & Doug & they're the perfect size) and fake food as well. Assembly took me & my hubby about 4 hours working together only stopping for a quick dinner & to put our toddler to bed. It wasn't too hard, just time consuming as there is a ton of parts. title: Quality took a nosedive - made two new doors
text: My MIL has one of these at her house. She bought it about 5-6 years ago. My nephews are really hard on it as is my daughter when she visits and, aside from the knobs on the stove no longer functioning, it's still in great shape. So MIL bought the set for my daughter too. Within a week, with us watching, my two year old pulled the dishwasher door apart. The particle board just disintegrated. She was not being rough with it - just opening it. We contacted the company who sent a replacement door. The replacement didn't match the rest of the set. It too broke within a week. The same thing happened with the refrigerator door. She opened it (she wasn't being rough) and it snapped at the hinges. The older set at my MIL's doesn't have the same issue. The quality of that one is much better than the new one. My husband is handy with wood. He wound up buying furniture grade plywood, re-using the hardware (including "ice machine" plastic), and making new doors. (lower fridge and dishwasher). They don't match perfectly, but they are much better than the garbage doors the set came with. I expect that he will have to replace the other two doors at some point in time so they will all match eventually.

text: So when I told my husband I wanted to get our 4 and 1 year old kids a play kitchen he looked like I had asked him to paint the house pink.
