My 4 year old loves that it looks a lot like our kitchen and has "called" all his cousins on the play phone to tell them what Santa brought. I hope it holds up well as they really love it.

title: Awesome kitchen!
text:
Purchased this as a Christmas gift for my children (1yo and 4yo). The reason I chose this over a more kiddy colorful option is because it's going in the living room and I didn't want it sticking out too much since my cabinets are Espresso. And to be honest, it looks better than my own kitchen!
Upon arrival, the box was half open which was concerning to say the least, since returning it (if damaged) would be quite the hassle. However, once opened, everything was still structurally sound and in good condition. Do be wary, it's heavy! After reading a few of the reviews about it taking roughly 4hrs to build, I offered my kids to my parents on Christmas Eve so that I had ample time to build in peace and quiet before the festivities began.
I started off by carefully separating each piece and wiping them clean. The biggest complaint I have is that there were foam particles all over the place. Granted it did its job of protecting the pieces but it was annoying to deal with. Directions were picture driven and was rather straightforward. The pieces were somewhat easy to locate - some took longer because they drew them larger than what they would appear to be when looking at other pictures. I incorrectly installed some parts because the orientation of some parts was the same on both sides with a small variance but was easy enough to correct. In order to speed up my process, I did use a power drill with 3lb of torque on the parts that required screws. That setting seemed to hold everything nicely without over-tightening and possibly cracking the wood by hand.
All in all, it took me 3hrs! Great timing but man, I felt like I ran a marathon! My back was killing me. The wood feels really solid and sturdy. I would say that this is probably the most precisely cut item I've ever built. Everything just lined up perfectly and fit without any correction. The only issue I see with the build are the small screws that hold the door latches that clip the doors close. They are very short, making it easy to strip from the wood. I already had to replace one that fell off when I reopened a tight door. I feel after a few uses, these will eventually pull off and that gluing them will be a better option.
Other than a few things such as it not having any electronics or handles to move it around, I'd have to give this 5/5 stars. For the price, it's absolutely worth it. Per other reviewers, I added some touch lights to the oven and above the sink to give it more realism. Might do the same for the fridge and/or microwave in the future. I supplied my kids with pots/pans/foods to go along with it. My kids love it and it's their favorite gift!

Upon opening the box I right away noticed some of the prices were slightly scratched, no big deal‚Ä¶ directions for assembly were mostly east to understand but it did take about 3-4 hours total to complete assemble. The faucet on the sink and the ice maker are both made of cheap soft plastic and both take the same included small blunt screws which really just tore up the plastic. The faucet I had to use a dremel attachment for my drill to pre-drill holes so the screws would actually catch and hold, even then I had to improvise with one of them using a longer screw and a washer. I‚Äôve maker, same issue but was in able to use a dremel or longer screws as it would have come through the front, I was gentle but still the plastic broke where the screws would be and i had to glue the ice maker in place, hopefully it holds. Definitely manufactured with very cheap materials..

All in all, it‚Äôs a cute kitchen but I don‚Äôt think it will last in the long run. Will likely become an outdoor toy and will be replaced after a month or two. Definitely not worth the price they ask for it, I could‚Äôve bought one at target for less money and better quality.

title: My 16 month grandson loves this kitchen set
text:
My daughter purchased this kitchen set for her 16 month old son. I volunteered to assemble this kitchen set. It arrived in a carton weighing 75lbs. It took me one hour to unpack, check and layout all the numbered parts. All the screws and small parts are in a blister pack clearly labeled. The set includes a hex key and a small wrench. The only other tool needed for assembly is a phillips head screwdriver.The unpacking was done last night in a spare upstairs unused room. It is best to do this assembly without any small children around to pick up any small parts.
At 9AM on a Saturday morning I was ready to begin.
The instructions are all pictures making assembly easy but although I am fairly handy it took me until 4 PM to complete this assembly. This included a few short breaks as well as a lunch break and a little play time with my grandson.
After the small parts were installed on the larger pieces, the large pieces were carried downstairs to be assembled in the play room. My grandson kept looking in as the assembly progressed.
He absolutely loves it.
Although assembly took quite some time I did enjoy putting this set together for him. It was worth every minute of my time to see the happy excited look on his face when he finally began to play with it.
Highly recommended.

Howard in New Jersey

text:

title: Screw holes off.
text:
Kids got this for Christmas from grandma. Have had my eye on this kitchen. Little did I know it would be a day project to put together! My kids were pestering me from noon to 6pm, is it fone yet?
There are different color screws so pay attention to that if you want to match the brown screw to the brown color where seen. And there are steps inside each step that need done first and in a certain order and there are no words in the instructions to tell you these things. You just find out when you have to take it apart again lol.
BUT THE MAJOR PROBLEM IS the screw holes on the inside fridge wall peice are off by almost 1/4 inch. And this causes the separator piece between the fridge and freezer and top of freezer to be installed on an angle so that the freezer door will not close. Very disappointed considering this was near the last of the steps and was all ready getting tired of putting it together. If I take the screws out on side above stove the shelf lays flat and the freezer can close (see pics)

title: Great Toy. You should buy it. Get ready to spend some time putting it together.
text:
Great toy. Lots of fun. Solid materials and well made. However: I‚Äôm a carpenter and it took me 3 and a half hrs to put this thing together. You MUST follow the instructions to the ‚ÄúT‚Äù and be prepared to screw or snap EVERY SINGLE PART together. Nothing comes preassembled.

Other than that - it‚Äôs awesome.

title: Really Nice Play Kitchen
text: This play kitchen is just as pictured.  The package is very heavy because the kitchen is made of good quality materials.  It takes several hours to assemble but actually comes with extra fittings (screws, bolts) so that you will not find yourself missing anything as you assemble it.  When assembled, all of the doors work very well and the knobs make realistic sounds (clicking).  We have only had it for a few days but so far it is a wonderful playset, especially for the price.

title: Some parts missing but nice overall
text: A few minor pieces were missing so thus the four versus five star review. By the time we laid everything out and began assembling, it wasn‚Äôt really prudent to stop, box it up and process a return for a few missing bits. However - isn‚Äôt it a minimal ask that ALL pieces be included? It took 3 hours to assemble with power tools.  Lots of work but the kitchen is nice. I hope it holds up - our toddler son is quite exuberant and physical with his toys... :) All in all, seems like good value for what you get. B+

text: This is great, looks good and seems it would last. It only took me about an hour and half to put together. Lots of little pieces, but the finished product is worth it.

title: Needs time and care but worth it in the end
text: It really does take 4-6 hours to build. It's hard to believe that there's people who did it in 3. One precaution to take is to remember that it's a toy and not real furniture. Don't overdo it when screwing on the parts or else the wood will break (esp when using a power drill). Also, don't drop any of the pieces because the wood will chip. If you treat the wood pieces with care, the finished product will look great. I doubt that there's a more aesthetically pleasing kitchen set for the price. Also, try to put it together when your kid's not around. Our toddler would not stay away and his curiosity ended in a couple of scratches. It was a pain to build but very satisfied with the end result. I would recommend it to anyone with a 2-4/5 year old.

title: I was initially disappointed in it due to its small size
text: We had the KidKraft white retro kitchen set for the last 5 years. I was initially disappointed in it due to its small size. It held up long enough, but eventually just completely fell apart. I wanted to replace it with a Pottery Barn set for both large size and better quality. I reluctantly purchased this set because of the cost. I was THRILLED today assembling it. It is much larger than the Retro set we had and so much sturdier. The directions can be tricky, you just need to pay close attention to detail (screws vary in color for inside vs. outside but are not labeled). I assembled it myself, no need for help, within 2 hours. I bought the washer and dryer set as well, not as sturdy, but absolutely adorable together!

Apparently you have 90 from purchased to report manufacturing defects.  This is a decent product otherwise, my 2 and 4 year old boys do love it.  It takes quite a while to put together, I did this myself and estimate 6-8 hours.  Assembly did have some challenges, but these products typically do.

title: Damaged and poorly patched by manufacturer and shipped as a new item!!
text: I bought this item for my children's birthday and planned on putting it together right before the party so they could play with it with all of their friends.  Today I opened it to begin putting it together and only took out 5 pieces.  3 out of these 5 pieces are clearly damaged and it is obvious that the company KNEW they were damaged and instead of recycling the pieces and providing new pieces and therefor a quality product, they did a slapdash job of smearing some stain/paint/whatever over the damaged places and threw them in the box with everything else.  I'm not even going to bother taking any of the other pieces out.  I'm outside of the window for returns since I waited until now to unbox the item (bad planning on my part, clearly).  I should have gone ahead and opened the box right when it arrived to make sure it was as it was supposed to be--my mistake for expecting to receive a product that wasn't damaged and poorly patched.  Pictures are attached, including a picture of how much of the toy is still in the box.

text: The instructions were a tad bit difficult to interpret since there were no words. I believe the dark colored screws should be used if it will be seen on the outside and the silver ones you would use elsewhere. It took 2 of use about 3 1/2 hours to put it together. My boys LOVE this play kitchen!! Just make sure you have a play area for it, as they will need space. I have only one complaint - there are C screws (24 silver and 14 bronze) and the directions don‚Äôt tell you which ones to use where, so since the kitchen it silver and brown I used the screws according to color of the piece (I ended up being one bronze screw short and had to use silver in its place, which only bothers me with my OCD!)
Otherwise this product is perfect. Came in perfect condition. Labeleled well. Very clear instructions (just need patience and common sense). I love putting things together and I enjoyed the first 3hrs of it ü§£ü§£. MUST BUY with all Melissa & Doug kitchen accessories üëå

text: My 3 1/2-year-old daughter is absolutely crazy about this kitchen set. I have had it only for a few days but she has almost played with it nonstop. Overall the set seems pretty sturdy. It also is one of the better looking sets but her but I have seen. Caution: this product took me 3 1/2 hours with no break to put together. The instructions or pictures only with no words, so I was left to my own ingenuity to figure out some of the steps and even witch and was up at times. Some of the screws are brown and some are silver the brown screws are clearly for the exterior the silver screws are for the interior. However, the instructions don‚Äôt indicate which screws go on which parts and it is unclear which pieces Will end up on the interior versus exterior. Therefore, I had to replace some of the screws when I thought the project was completed. There are 174 total screws bolts nuts and clasps. So, if this is a gift do not wait until the night before to put it together.  Other than that, I would highly recommend this product it inspires imagination in play!

title: Takes time to put together but well worth it!
text:
This is a super cute kitchen! We got this for our daughter for her 2nd birthday. She's a very tall kiddo and we wanted something that would accommodate her height. It did take me about 4 hours to put together, but I feel that it was well worth it. I would much prefer to have to spend some time putting something together that will last and stay together than snapping cheap plastic together. This feels very sturdy. I don't worry that she will be able to drag this around the house or easily tip it on to herself. It did arrive looking like it was backed over by a truck. There was a damaged piece, but I called the company and they shipped a replacement out no problem! ***I will add more to my review once my daughter has had a chance to play with this toy more****
***UPDATE***
My daughter has had this for a month now. She LOVES this kitchen!! It is the perfect size for her to both enjoy now and grow into a bit (she's about 37" tall and just turned 2). She likes to put things in the microwave and has every one wash their hands in the little sink. I like that it has a little bar on the side for a dish towel. I found that if I stick a couple self adhesive hooks on the side, it makes for a perfect spot to put her Apron and chefs hat. I definitely recommend this kitchen. It has lots of space to store play food and dishes. It is very sturdy (I have a rather destructive child and it has survived her thus far). If you are looking for play food, I highly recommend the learning resources new sprouts play food which works great in terms of size with this kitchen and the ikea duktig pots and pans and utensils match up well in size too.

title: Sturdy kitchen

title: Really nice!
text: This kitchen is very nice. I wanted to kichen for my 2 boys ages 2 and 4, and found this online. I like it because it is very gender neutral and it was one of the tallest i had seen reviewed, this was important to me as my kids are tall for their ages. The kitchen is plenty big enough for 2 kids to play comfortably. It was a little challenging to put together, but the end result is very nice. Would recommend!

title: Fantastic!
text:
This play kitchen is awesome! I spent DAYS researching and reading reviews for play kitchens before settling on this one. I had narrowed my search down to either this one or the smaller KidKraft kitchen, but finally caught a good price for this one and went for it. After purchasing it, receiving it and assembling it, I ran into the smaller version in a store. Boy was it small! I have a tall 2.5 year old, and I don't think he would've fit at that other kitchen for much longer. SO pleased that we went with the larger kitchen for a little more money.

This kitchen has tons of storage space for all those tiny items you buy to go along with it. That was the main reason we chose this kitchen. The plastic options don't have much for storage, and I don't know about other parents out there, but we already have enough toys laying around the house. I don't need all the small plastic food and utensils strung about the house either. Additionally, this kitchen is so much more realistic and sturdy. My son is very particular and LOVES when his toys completely mimic adult items, like tools, vacuum cleaners, brooms, tractors, trucks. You name it, he wants it to be like the real thing! So this kitchen is great. It's not an eyesore and it looks a lot more like Mommy & Daddy's kitchen. The quality is great. I fear one of those plastic kitchens would only take a couple years of toddler abuse before needing to be tossed. This kitchen, however, will likely be passed down to grandchildren or kept around for grandchildren someday.

As other reviewers have noted, it does take a long time to assemble. My husband and I tackled it in about 2-3 hours one evening after the boys were in bed, and we had no issues. We had one problem with a piece - the 2 pieces that hold the towel bar were not drilled correctly so we weren't able to attach it. Very minor annoyance, and I'm sure if we contacted KidKraft they would send replacement pieces out immediately (as they've done for other reviewers). But, quite frankly, we added that to the to-do list and just never got around to it.

Overall, very pleased with the purchase, quality, and design of this product. It's sturdy, large enough for several children, and will last and grow with them due to it's size and construction. Love it! I highly recommend! It's definitely worth the extra money!

title: Looks nice, would never order again
text:
We bought this kitchen because it matched our boys furniture. It looks different from the rest and we were excited to set it up. The box weighs more than an average woman can lift. 85lbs I believe. Then we opened it and saw that EVERY SINGLE SCREW had to be assembled. There was over a hundred screws and 40-50 pieces. It took two people (who are pretty intelligent and regulars at put together furniture) over 3 hours. That is no exaggeration. It may have been closer to 4. We gave up one night and went back at it the next day. I am certain we had an argument at some point because we were both so frustrated.

Once assembled it is a charming little kitchen. Again, just know going into it that assembly is difficult and a little confusing. It almost requires two people to balance pieces. I will say that the paint finish is a little disappointing. The silver scratches very easily. My two toddlers are not rough on things and yet they have already worn some off in a few weeks. I scratched a few pieces during assembly as well.

So all in all, aside from the unique look, I would not recommend this over another play kitchen for the money.

title: Excellent for little chefs!
text: My grandson, almost 2 1/2, wants to be "just like daddy" and daddy is a fabulous cook!  So, this item which matches their kitchen (appliance and cabinet color) seemed a likely choice.  The item arrived and was well packed; items were labeled with small stickers indicating their part number.  The only issue we had was that the directions are ALL in pictures with no written directions at all.  This makes sense as there are a number of languages this would need to be translated to, however, it did make for a rather long assembly process.  If you are purchasing this, PLEASE be aware of the hardware; it comes on a "bubble card" that is labeled with the part letter and number included.  What they don't tell you is that there are different colors of the same size in the same "bubble" some are dark colored to go with the wood tone, others to go with the appliance tone.  There are also a few pieces that have slight size differences.  We made a couple of poor choices and ended up having to improvise.  It took about four hours and at times six hands to fully assemble it (a power drill with multiple drill heads helped A LOT) , but, the look on his face when he saw it....PRICELESS!!!!  He has used it just about non stop.  It's very sturdy, come with a strap to attach to the wall for safety and is quite attractive.  if I could give a 4.5 or even 4.75 star rating I would but the direction issue and hardware labeling issue prevents a 5.

title: EXCEEDED MY EXPECTATIONS! SO WORTH THE MONEY!
text:
The kitchen was packaged and shipped very carefully. All of the pieces arrived undamaged. Once the kitchen is assembled it has quite a bit of weight to it and it is very sturdy! I'm very impressed with with quality of this product! I will admit putting this kitchen together was a little overwhelming at first and it took several hours. I would recommend having at least one other person to help. No matter how frustrating it is believe me, it is worth it!.I really love how this kitchen doesn't have any stickers. I absolutely hate how all of the plastic kitchens have stickers all over them. The graphics on this kitchen are painted on which is awesome in my book! Also all of the oven and stove knobs click when turned. The sink handle moves up and down. The only thing I dislike about the sink is that the sink basin shifts. I plan on using some glue under the lip to fix that issue though. The paper towel/hand towel holder is great other than the fact that the stick is way smaller than the holes so it is easily removed by nearly 2 year old. I just don't like the idea of my son running around the house with a wooden stick. This shouldn't be a problem with older children. My absolute favorite part of this kitchen is the stove burners. They are made out of 2 different pieces of plastic which give it a realistic look. The counter top is white with silver speckles. The espresso colored laminate particle board has a wood grain finish which is absolutely beautiful! All of the silver colored appliances have no wood grain which also gives this kitchen a more realistic look. The "gray brick" backsplash is made of laminated particle board as well which was a pleasant surprise. I thought it was going to be laminated cardboard.

The counter height of the kitchen is 22 inches
The counter length is 32 inches
The inner width of the freezer and fridge is 10 inches
The overall height of the kitchen is approximately 40.5 inches

The play food and play pots and pans in the photos are by Learning Resources. Although their play food can be a bit pricey it is the most realistic play food on the market and perfectly sized of little hands.

title: Solid kids kitchen
text:
This was a gift for my kids for Christmas and they love it. I chose KidKraft because we've had good experiences with other items from the brand and this is no exception. The structure itself is solid and sturdy, and the assembly was fairly straightforward, but there were many components to keep track of. Most of the kitchen is wood and the finishings are plastic (handles, windows for the oven and microwave, sink, faucet etc)
Definitely grab a drill for this, the screws are tightly fitted so I'm confident they won't loosen over time. The play food that comes with it is not the greatest quality, a little flimsy, but it's a nice little set to start off with. Overall I would recommend and purchase again.

title: Quality and accuracy of description are off
text: The quality of this is okay. There was considerable scuffs and damages to most of the pieces, but luckily not too noticeable once it is together. The phone I received looks more like a cell phone and nothing like the one in the picture. The description also says it has a turntable in the microwave. Mine does not. It does take some time to put together. I'm pretty good at following picture instructions, I always put together Ikea furniture and it took me 3 hours. The only problem I ran into was that on some hardware there are two different colors of the same item. The directions don't tell you which ones to use so you have to use your best judgement or it'll look weird. I didn't realize this at first and had to go back and replace some with the correct color. But it does look nice. Not an eyesore. Just the right size. Just poor execution on their part. But it was a gift and either way I know my kids will love it!

title: We love our KidKraft Uptown Espresso Kitchen Playset!
text:
Received Monday. I (Elisabeth) spent about 3-4 hours on Tuesday to put it together. My daughter received it as her fourth birthday present on Thursday after months of requesting. We are in love with it.

1. Aesthetically very pleasing. The only place we had for it was in our living room. We chose this set because it gets fantastic reviews, but also because it worked with our d√©cor and doesn't look like a big clunky toy in the middle of the room. We also love that it's gender neutral. It's like a "real" modern kitchen. I daycare out of our home, so this will be an exciting toy for many years.

2. Quality. This thing came as a kit, but the hardware and materials are of amazing quality. Done correctly, and played with basic care, this set should last for years and years to come. Very solid set that should be able to take the abuse the kids will throw at it.

3. Features. Fridge/freezer OR cupboard, ice maker, chalk board, microwave, back splash, hanging knobs, burners, stove and oven knobs "click click" when turned, sink with moveable faucet and handle, dishwasher/cupboard, oven, towel rack. Lots to do.

4. Storage. We bought a large pack of food. Also bought a package of little storage containers that coordinated with the set to put the food in. Got everything in the fridge and freezer with room to spare. We also ordered a pot and pan set, but were disappointed with it. We are returning it for a better set, but there will be plenty of room for it in the dishwasher. My daughter had a tea set and picnic set that she's already brought out to play, and they sit prettily on top or on the shelf. Lots of storage left for some more pieces (dishes, dish rack, chef outfit, mixer, etc), probably for Christmas.

Cons
1. I read some reviews that state the doors are hard to get on if they get wrenched off. I can see this being an issue. I do believe that if you run into this problem, you'll have to loosen some bolts and screws to slide the door back on and then retighten them. I hope we don't have a door bust off, but if we do that will be my plan of action.

title: Five Stars

title: NOT WORTH IT
text: The box is 60lbs. You cannot move the box, or assemble this kitchen without help. AND if you choose to assemble this with a partner or spouse, you may or may not be speaking at the end of the 4-6 hour endeavor.  Not only that, it's very frustrating to realize when you're halfway through that pieces are missing. Getting KidKraft to send those pieces that they didn't put in the box? Very difficult. We received this as a gift (by a friend who must hate us), but if we were purchasing on our own we would just go with the an easy-assembly, plastic kitchen. Our 2-year old would never know the difference, and I wouldn't have 48 pieces (and 200 screws) sitting in my living room while I wait for KidKraft to get back to me about the missing parts. Bottom line: IT'S JUST NOT WORTH IT (unless you can pay someone to assemble it for you...then it may be worth it).

title: Love it!!!
text: [[VIDEOID:b902610d22d376fa4881ab444e2294bf]] We LOVE this kitchen. It won't show as a verified purchase because it was a gift from my parents to my son. He's 19 months old and every time we went to someone's house he would always play with their toy kitchen and I was super surprised that he had such an imagination already. Back to the kitchen... it took me (a mechanic by trade) 4 hours to put it together, so be prepared... it's not difficult just tedious and intricate and could use two people on some sections though I made it work with just myself. For some sections you have silver hardware and others brown--pay attention to when you're using the silver or the brown because at the very end you need 5 brown screws for the top and I only had silver left and because I'm anal, I went back and got the brown screws out of different sections just so I could have them for the top. This unit has some weight to it which is the main reason I asked the grands to get this versus the plastic ones.. my son is a wild animal and would rip those apart in a heartbeat. All pieces came intact and no items were damaged. We love this kitchen and feel like it will last him for at least the next three years or so.

title: It is durable and looks like my kid will have a lot of fun with ...

She was role-playing in visited toddler kitchens since she was about 14 months. Now she has her own kitchen. The only differences between this and a more realistic kitchen is the oven door and dishwasher door swing open from the sides instead of dropping down. I suppose they can double as storage cabinets instead. Unfortunately, the towel bar is not fixed in place and she has figured out how to remove it. Other than that I still give it a 5 stars for quality in construction, easy to assemble, wipes clean and is lots of pretend cooking fun!

title: Nice Kitchen, lots of labor of love
text: Very nice looking kitchen. Good size for my 18 month old, who is about 35 inches tall. She still has to tippy toe to reach the sink and stove but she has fun with the cabinets. Great price for a child to grow into. Sturdy so it seems it will last long. Total time to build was 4 hours by myself (30 min inventory, 3.5 hours building Time). Tedious, lots of pieces, but instructions were pretty straight forward. BEWARE: some screws are colored BROWN to match with the wood, and some are SILVER to match with the other pieces. No where in the instructions do they indicate which one to use. Just be mindful of that when choosing your screws. Also, I am a small petite woman, and still broke a peice of a screw/wood off when tightening, so do not tighten too hard when screwing the nail into the wood. Overall a good buy, though I would personally never want to build this thing again.

title: Nice Little Kitchen.
text: I purchased this kitchen for my step daughter for her 5th birthday. 1st the pros: it's a nice kitchen. Looks modern and fairly real as far as play kitchens go. The finish is nice and after put together seems pretty sturdy. Here are my issues with the kitchen: 1. I wish the instructions were just a but more detailed. It wasn't hard to put together, just time consuming. The instructions only have illustrations, no words telling you what to do. Just me, but I think it could have been a lot easier to assemble with actual directions along with the illustrations. 2. Three of the pieces of our kitchen were damaged. One of the boards inside the fridge has a crack (not a big deal since it's not really seen) but the top shelf is cracked completely from one side to the other and it's pretty noticeable. There was also a small chip in the countertop. 3. Not that it's a huge deal, but for over $100 I think you should be able to press the buttons in. The knobs turn and that's cool, but everything else is just painted on. Or hard plastic parts. I've had other (way cheaper) kitchens that have buttons that press in. Just my thoughts. Kids like things the more real they seem. And paint on a board is just sort of blah for the money spent. All in all I think it's a cool looking kitchen and believe my girl will enjoy playing with it. Hopefully we will get a lot of use out of it. I took a star away for the damaged pieces, and another for all the other stuff. (Buttons & instructions)

title: Patience Required
text:
I bought this after reading hundreds of reviews for various kitchen play sets. The single most important factor in making my decision was that I didn't want it to be too short/small for my toddler to use for any length of time. Luckily, while she is tall (38 inches), this kitchen is taller, and I feel she will be able to play with it for a couple of years at least. The second factor while purchasing was that this was one of the few kitchens with a non-obnoxious color scheme. We are keeping the play set close to our actual kitchen so I can keep an eye on things, and this kitchen does not draw the eye with loud colors.

Yes, it takes a while to assemble. My husband and I are pretty decent at putting things together, and it took us both three solid hours to assemble this kitchen. As some reviewers have mentioned, pay attention to the colored screws. They go on the panels that face outward. It just makes everything look prettier.

Separate compartments for the freezer, fridge, oven and dishwasher mean your child has plenty of storage space to stow play food and accessories (not included).

The play set seems pretty solid, and my toddler has to exert some force to open and close the doors. I'm sure that will loosen up in time though.

I took off a star because our set came without the towel bar on the side. I'm going to call KidKraft and let them know; if they give me a prompt resolution I will change my rating.

Overall I feel this was a worthwhile purchase and I'd recommend it to a friend.

title: It is very realistic and the girls love it! It arrived in a box that would ...
text: My wife purchased this for a 5 and 3 year old.  It is very realistic and the girls love it!  It arrived in a box that would make you think that it isn't going to be as big as the pictures make it look, but don't be deceived.  It is packed extremely well to preclude damage in shipment and the parts needed for assembly are packed for easy identification as you progress through the assembly schematic/instructions.  You really need 2 people to put this together as one will need to hold the sections in place as the other secures bolts, screws, etc.  Expect 4+ hours assembly time!!!  My only complaint is - the little phone attachment wouldn't snap into place.  Hopefully the company will replace that part.  Otherwise, it was perfect!

title: It's a cute little kitchen and it seems very sturdy. I would have given it 5 stars at ...
text:
The other reviews are right. FOUR. HOURS. It's a cute little kitchen and it seems very sturdy. I would have given it 5 stars at this point if- 1- the instructions were written out and more clear, and 2- one of the holes had lined up better. Something caused the holes for one of the shelves in the refrigerator to line up incorrectly, so the door sticks a bit. Every other piece of assembly up to that point went smoothly, it just took a long time.

Advise for assembly: 1. USE A DRILL. 2. On step 27 it tells you to put the right wall for the microwave on. Do this BEFORE you put on the shelf that acts as the bottom of the microwave, or your screwdriver/drill (like mine) won't fit under it to put it on and you'll be cursing kidkraft for a little bit.

Since this kitchen doesn't have lights or sound, I bought battery operated GE LED touch activated puck lights and stuck them to the underside of the inside of the fridge and oven. The one for the oven, I colored over the light with a red sharpie and let dry overnight (the lights are cool to the touch) so that the oven glows red inside. It was a cheap $10 upgrade and my kid loves turning the oven on and off now.

title: This is a quality product & what we got is what was described and offered, except it exceeded my expectations.
text: This is a quality product. I have assembled a lot of stuff over the years and I am very impressed with the quality of this product. The assembly hardware itself is of a very high quality for this level of toy.  That does not mean that it is not constructed with materials that can be damaged during the assembly process if you over tighten or don't take the time to line up and or thread the fasteners properly. I only had one goof while putting it together in that some of the screws are silver and some are painted to blend in with the unit and had to repeat one step. Also my box was in very bad shape when it was left at my house and I was very happy to find that the measures the manufacturer took to ensure that it would not be damaged all worked. My only wish that I have for the industry would be to offer a larger scale unit which I would be happy to pay for. Most of the larger units are in the molded plastic family and not our preference. As far as the other negative comments on the assembly go I take most of those with a grain of salt as I am sure those who assemble items like this have different skill levels. I find that if I take a good bit of time on the front end sorting the parts then the assembly goes much smoother. Every time I hit a snag I just took a moment to line up each of the features on the plans and except for the screw colors it all went to gather perfectly. What we got is what was described and offered, except it exceeded my expectations.

An excellent product. I would buy from KidKraft again.

It's the perfect size for her at 2 years old and will easily grow with her over the next few years. We ended up buying the Learning Resources basket meals to go with it because it had a nice variety and was fantastic quality.

I read several bad reviews regarding assembly... but they left me scratching my head. Yes, there are LOTS of pieces. Yes, it will take you a solid couple hours. But we knew that when we bought it and set aside the time to work on it. Also, don't be stupid and assemble it the night before gifting it. That's just asking for frustration. For us, everything fit together perfectly and we had no damaged or blemished pieces.

title: Clear your Calendar before attempting assembly
text: Took me 4 hours, yes you heard me 4 hours to assemble.  This is because every piece of trim you see, cabinet handles, nobs ect. all require assembly, nothing is bolted to any panel so everything that sticks out has to be attached separately.  I spent 45 minutes just on the 1st page.  If you enjoy assembling ikea furniture you will be right at home with this although the instructions are too sparse for my liking.  Something like this should be 30+ pages, this one has 15ish.  As mentioned by other reviewers, some screws of the same letter have different colors but the instruction does not make clear which you are suppose to use.  Other than that and the time it takes to assemble everything seems to be good quality.  A few nicks from shipping but nothing major.  DO NOT OVER TIGHTEN anything, this is a sturdy toy but too much torque will result in some connecting areas failing.  I did not have any but I can tell there are areas that would have given way if I kept tightening.  One thing that kept it from being 5 was there is a slight gap between the final horizontal piece that forms the top of the microwave and connects to the rod at the end.  Maybe I missed something but I was pretty careful I thought.  Any way still a great looking set that my daughter loves and her opinion is really the only one that matters.

title: Assembly instructions and quality control need work
text:
Since this is a Christmas gift, I have no play activity to report (yet), so just reviewing assembly.

As other reviewers have noted, this item takes a substantial investment of time to assemble (think of an overly complicated Ikea bookshelf) even with access to ratchets and power tools. Some of the milling on the wooden parts is imprecise, making the last few assembly steps (notably the back of the fridge and the top of the microwave), much more difficult to "square up" than they should have been.

The biggest problem though, is the flimsy door latches supplied for all 5 "appliance" doors. The screw holes are milled too large, or the supplied screws are too tiny, so that in 3 of the 5 cases (dishwasher, microwave, oven), the first time the door is latched, pulling it open again pulled the latch off the door and left it in the cabinet "grabber" with screws exposed. I haven't yet reached out to the manufacturer, but I don't see much of a solution available - replacing the doors with ones with smaller milled holes will require me to at least partially disassemble the unit - sending replacement latches or screws of the same size will just repeat the problem.

Still "playable" without latches, but not as realistic or as safe, in my opinion.

It seems a shame for a product with such a high cost and which looks so nice to be undone by flimsy $0.01 pieces of plastic, but there you go. Shipping the doors and framing pieces with latches and drawer slides and knobs preassembled would have been a good way to avoid these problems.

I will update this review with any resolutions provided.

title: Not an easy assembly....buyer beware
text:
Solid product BUT not easy to assemble, Be warned if you've never assembled furniture ie. entertainment system, desk, dresser(s), etc. There is no written directions except pictures which should be enlarged. IF you do not assemble some of the last pieces in the correct order, (step 22) you'll be taking the unit apart more than together. Also, some of the heads of the screws are brown others metal finish. Depending where the screws will be used, exposed or hidden you want to use the brown instead of the metal finish. They don't tell you, you have to figure that out yourself. The total assemble time for me was close to 3 hours and that was me solo. I also would consider myself on the high end of intermediate/advanced assembler given my 20 years of experience assembling toys and furniture. This was not fun!
On the positive side, it finally came together and it is solid. I'm sure this will be part of the family & household for many many years. The kids are loving it. Good luck

title: for starters it took a good while to arrive at my house
text:
Well, for starters it took a good while to arrive at my house, I ordered it on Dec 26th the estimated delivery was Dec. 31st it didn't arrive until Jan. 3rd. Maybe it was because of the holiday. Although I have NEVER had issues with deliveries around the holidays.

When I opened the package and was getting all the materials out I noticed that the screw package was open....What a nightmare that was as screws were stuck into the foam around the package and laying all over the package...100 screw pick-up/find...There was a few screws missing because of this, luckily they provided extra screws which made up for the screws that were missing thankfully.

Once we started putting it together my husband noticed that the hinges on the microwave door were on the wrong way (images provided). Luckily my husband is mister fix it and was able to get the brads off and screw the hinge on correctly.

The other pieces were in moderate condition. The edges of the pieces of wood were somewhat scraped and nicked (could've been from the screws being loose in the package, no idea really).

Overall, this product was not up to the KidKraft standards that I held for the company. the Dollhouse that I bought my daughter was in immaculate condition. Since I paid nearly he same amount of money for the Kitchen as I did for the dollhouse (3 dollar difference) I expected the same or better quality.

However, even with the problems in packaging, the hinges and the scrapes on the edges of the wood my daughter LOVES the kitchen. The built product looks great (images provided) in my daughters room despite it all.

I will purchase from KidKraft again despite this issue.

It took my husband 2 hours to build the Kitchen. Not including time taken to get the brads out of the hinge to correct the mistake.

title: Build with patience...
text:
I want to start off by saying why I'm only giving this product 4 stars (though I really wanted to give it 5). The instructions leave a lot to be desired. It took three adults reading them to really understand where the parts went, how they were supposed to attach. The pictures were detailed, but it would have been even nicer to include written instructions right alongside the pictures. Also, the box that it came in was very beat up. I purchased this 3 weeks before my son's 3rd birthday, but due to the condition of the box, I had to put it together right away. There were two pieces that were scuffed up but they were in the middle of other pieces in the box so this occurred at their packaging plant and not from the shipping. Despite the box looking like someone tried to eat it for lunch, the parts inside (with the exception of the two previously mentioned) were well packed and in good condition. There was also a very confusing spot with the back splash (see picture below). The picture instructions do not accurately show where the big grey box goes. We were lucky and figured it out so there was no disassembling to fix it.

Now, the overall quality of the product seems to be fantastic. It is very well put together and unlike some products doesn't feel loose or wiggle when my boys play with it. There is a ton of storage within the kitchen. We've only had the product for two days. However, my almost 3yr old is "The Great Destroyer" and the fact that it has lasted this long speaks volumes.

Side note... when writing a birthday message for your kid before you attach it to the finished product, you might want to make sure it is going the correct direction.

This kitchen comes with a freezer, fridge, (with built in ice maker) oven, dishwasher (that holds a removable cutting board), microwave, towel holder, phone (that looks an awful lot like an iPhone), 4 burners, sink, faucet. Everything that a child needs in their own, mini sized kitchen.

title: Classy Kitchen Toy
text:
The only downfall to this unit was the packaging and poor handling. Because this unit weighs in at about 75 lbs it is suceptable to shipping damage. In my case it was extensive damage resulting in transfer damage to the actual product inside the package. There were roughly 10 softball size holes on the package I received. Several panels inside the package were scratched along the sides and the bottom inside panel that spans the entire unit was moderately bowed. The box had one small piece of tape left in tact holding the top of the cardboard lid on. When I picked it up to bring inside the house everything inside nearly fell out. I called amazon and since it was a 3rd party vendor all they would do was pay UPS to ship back and have them pick up, but for $160 and being a prime item I felt that there should be more wiggle room considering I received a damaged product. My refund would have been 7-13 days and my next order would arrive after my daughters birthday. Eventually after 1.5 hours of negotiaons I recieved a 50% refund of the product and a garunteed full reimbursement if the product inside was damaged beyond a reasonable amount (which varies person to person). I was satisfied with the outcome of the situation and assembled the unit this evening.

Assembly was fairly easy and straight forward. About 2 hours total to put together and only a few minor issues with the flow of the install instructions. A stubby Phillips screwdriver will come in handy in a couple areas of assembly as will a drill with a Allen head apex bit size 5/32". The only main area of concern is the tray for the play oven. The opening of the oven door (which swings open like a cabinet, instead of dropping down like a real oven) prevents the easy install and remove of the tray within the channeled bracket. I simply placed the tray on top of the groved bracket to make removal for sanitizing easier. If you manipulate the install flow and save the inner bracket for last the tray will be permenetly installed and not removable without removing 2 Phillips screws and the bracket. A minor issue that doesn't change the quality of this toy. It is a nice toy that my 2 year old will simply love to play with for a long time. Very happy with the overall outcome of my purchase and would purchase again knowing all of the above.

I hope others find this review helpful.

text:
My daughter received this for her second birthday and I have to say it was by far her favorite gift. She was cooking "soup" for everyone right after opening it and didn't want to go to bed because wanted to "play more kitchen!".

She always pretends to cook while I make dinner so I wanted something that she could use along side me which meant it needed to be in the dining room and therefore relatively attractive. This definitely fit the bill as it looks lovely and we've received many compliments on it.

Some minor complaints but nothing that would deter me from recommending this to a friend.

- Doors to oven and dishwasher are difficult for my toddler to pull open. Dad will be figuring something to loosen the little latch things.
- Oven/disherwasher both open to the side instead of up and down like the real thing. I wonder if this is because kids sit on a break them if they open downwards? I thought this would bother my daughter for not being realistic but she doesn't seem to care.
- Takes a very long time to assemble. My husband and father-in-law spent 2 hours doing this together. They're both engineers and very handy but it was still quite the project for them.

title: Good quality, takes time to assemble.
text:
This is a good quality playset. Sturdy, well designed and all the parts fit each other well.
As everybody has mentioned, putting it together takes time. I know my way around the furniture assembly, and still it took me good 2.5 hours.
A few tips:
- Power screwdriver is must.
- You'll need phillips and a hex bits.
- Do not overtighten; you may damage the panels.
- Important: some screws and fasteners come in 2 colors - stainless and bronze. Bronze should go to the sides that are seen from outside (to match the panels). You got to have some good spacial perception and planning to see which screws to use where.
Good luck!

text:
We bought this for my daughter, while we were out of town my brother came over and built this for my daughter. Actually on the dishwasher the door was drilled on opposite sides so he had to drill his own hole in order to assemble the product correctly.

After we saw the product it looks absolutely amazing. I cannot tell you about sturdiness because my daughter will not be able to play with it until tomorrow. I will attempt to update my review at a later time if i remember.

Overall the product is worth it, especially for the 129.99 price. Most kitchen sets around this or cheaper are pure crap. The tile on the back of the kitchen looks real, also so does the "Marble" counter tops. I would highly recommend this purchase for any child, especially if you plan on putting this in your own kitchen and dinning room and want something that looks descent.

I would of given this four stars for overall if it did not take my brother close to 4-5 hours of assembly time. (Also as noted the box they chip it in is pure crap. The sides were falling apart when we received the item.)

*****UPDATE 06/23/2014*****
My daughter has now used this product for almost a year, I would say this product has held up to my tough standards. title: Gorgeous kitchen, headache to set up
text:
I snatched up this kitchen when I saw it on sale. It had been on my radar for a while as a potential birthday gift for my daughter. My husband and I built it last night and it came out beautiful, but was a headache to set up. Some of the pieces did not match up such as the latch for the microwave door and my husband had to drill new holes instead of using the prefabricated holes in order to make the door latches line up when closed (we could have asked for another door but it would have halted further assembly and would take up to 5 days to arrive). There was also 2 sets of screws missing, but I called the company this morning and they are shipping out the missing parts free of charge. I was quite impressed that they answered after the first ring. I suspect missing parts are a common occurrence as they had a whole sheet come with the product detailing how to contact them for missing parts.
Anyway, the set up was a pain and made for a long profanity filled night. We have assembled many other toys and furniture ourselves before but this product was was full of assembly issues. Some of the directions did not make sense in terms of the order they want you to put the pieces in place. For example, the instructions did not tell you to slide the backing for the refrigerator in place untill after everything was screwed in tight. This resulted in us having to unscrew certain screws to loosen it up in order to fit the piece in and then screw everything back. The biggest headache was that assembly requires you to screw in a lot of the parts upside down blindly and with some of the last portions of set up the screw driver does not even fit in to small space to tighten things in so we had to improvise and use the drill portion of our swiss army knife. Overall, it took 3.5 hours to set up. They shipped everything in a compact box. All the knobs and parts that stick out had to be individually screwed in. Think Ikea assembly time times 10.
It is a beatiful product and my daughters will get a lot of use out of it. Compact but with enough storage for tons of playfood and cookware. My daughter is 2 years old and 70% percentile for height and can reach all the knobs and access all the doors (which do stick a little but probably will loosen after a while). There is enough counter and room space for multiple children and will probably last them till age 8-9 or whenever they get tired of pretend play. The design is aesthetically pleasing (looks more modern than my real kitchen) and can fit into any decor. I am pleased, but did not enjoy the set up.
Note that they will only cover replacements 90 days from purchase and there are no other warranties. Make sure you set it up soon after you get it so you know if you'll need replacement parts and don't throw out the sheet with the customer service number and item batch number.

title: Sturdy, Quality Product
text:
We bought this for our son last Christmas right when he turned 2. He's very large, so all the other play kitchens out there would have been too short for him. This one was definitely worth the extra money! It's nicer than my own kitchen, and my son has a great time telling me what he's cooking, and constantly opens and closes all the doors.

It did take my husband forever to set this up. He thought it would go much faster, so he didn't start putting it together until about 11pm Christmas eve, and he wasn't finished until around 3am. So make sure to leave plenty of time to put it together! However, even though it was a pain in the butt for him, he still says it was worth it.

Before making this purchase, because of the cost I put a lot of thought and research into it. My son is very into cooking and being in the kitchen, so I decided it was worth it. He has played with the kitchen every single day since Christmas, so it's already paid for itself. The kitchen looks just like it does in the pictures and he loves all the "high-end finishes." He's almost 3 now, and is as big as a 5-year-old, so I am glad we went with this kitchen, as he would have outgrown the others within weeks of getting them. We do also have an almost one-year-old who loves to play with the kitchen as well. It's lasted 8 months now under heavy playing by two boys, so I imagine it will hold up for another few years until they outgrow it.

Side note, if your kids make a huge mess and then someone drops by unexpectedly, you can also quickly shove a bunch of toys into all the cabinets and it makes a great storage facility as well!I

EDIT 10/2020: My boys played with this kitchen for 5 years, then we donated it to their younger cousins. They certainly weren't delicate with it, and after that long, only one knob had broken off. Definitely worth the price we paid.

title: Fun kitchen - but not as indestructable as I hoped
text:
We purchased this last year for Christmas. My husband and I are pretty much experts at assembling boxed furniture - but this one took about 2 1/2 hours to complete. The kitchen does seem well built when you put it together, but we quickly found that there are a few flaws with the design. They were:
1. Instead of attaching the hinge pieces on the doors with screws, the come riveted on from the factory. At first, this seemed great because it was one less step to complete to put it together. However, within 4 (yes 4) days of giving it to the kids, our oldest child (who is 4) ran into the open oven door, and broke it off at the hinge. While I could probably find a way to fix the door - I would have to completely disassemble the kitchen back to step 3 to re-install it.
2. The sink is able to be pulled out - but isn't really designed to be because of the way the plastic nubs that hold it in place... I'm expecting any day that those will break off
3. The towel bar is removable - which again seems good, but quickly became a sword for our son and needed to be removed
Other than that, our kids have fun with it, and it is a good size for them. Plus it does have lots of space to put dishes and play food, which is great.

title: Assembly is not for the faint of heart
text:
Our 4 ¬æ year old granddaughter had asked for a play kitchen about a month ago, so I ordered this with Plan Toys assorted fruits and vegetables, dMelissa and Doug's stainless steel pots and pans, and their Wooden Sandwich Making Set. As she had opened them before seeing the large box wrapped on the other side of the room, she said "But I really want a stove!". We all smiled.

The uptown espresso kitchen was every bit as good when completed as I had expected.

The box itself is extremely heavy, but everything is well packed and labeled. The instructions will seem familiar to anyone who has assembled lots of IKEA furniture, but they could have been more clear.

They don't use words, just numbers and pictures to describe what to do. So in certain diagrams. they are showing you few different parts to install before moving to the next diagram. But in some cases, the order in which you assemble those pieces matters.

There were several areas of particular trouble-
‚Ä¢Installing the countertop, which I wound up reinstalling maybe five times before getting it all right. When I thought I had it all done, I realized that you really need to pre-install the round pipe support that holds the right end of the microwave shelves before you install the counter, so that you have access to the screw under that piece.
‚Ä¢The low and upper shelf components for the Microwave. I had to go back an loosen a lot of fittings, in order to get the microwave door hinges to fit right within the two shelves, and then tighten them all up again.
‚Ä¢Installing the top and back panels of the Freezer required loosening everything and then tightening in a specific order.

Finally, when I looked over what pieces were remaining, I realized that I missed two latches, but fortunately, they were easy to install out of sequences.

As an architect, woodworker, and rather experienced assembler of things over the years, I was surprised that it took over four hours to assemble properly. Part of the reason is that pieces were strewn all over the living room floor, and with the chaos of Christmas, it was a little distracting. I chose to do this by myself, soliciting my granddaughter's help a few times to hold the doors in place while I assembled the upper shelves or aprons that held them in place. I also like things to fit well, ad in a few instances, I had to go back and loosen things so that everything could wiggle a little, and then tighten it all up again.

Would I buy it again? Absolutely. She loves it.

title: Kids love it! Assembly takes some time - very sturdy
text:
Both of my children love it! 4 years old and almost 2.... they can't get enough of clicking the dials for the stove, and using the working paper towel dispenser. We bought some of the Melissa / Doug cookware and other kitchen toys and they go together very well. This kitchen is sturdy and has a lot of detail. Highly recommend - however the assembly takes some time.
Assembly tips:
- Have a very large area ready for this install, on carpet if possible (garage floor or tile might scratch the dark finish) when you think that you have a large enough area, keep clearing floor space!
- The kitchen can easily be moved after assembly by 2 people.
- Use a drill / electric screwdriver with a 'low torque' setting, snug up screws by hand to avoid stripping the particle board. There are a LOT of fasteners, using a drill will really speed things up.
- There are brown fasteners and silver fasteners that will work with multiple steps in the directions, but the brown fasteners are for use in area where the wood is visible. This is not specified in the directions (at least I didn't see it)
- If you are unsure what orientation a part goes (the counter top support for example) look ahead in the directions. The later steps will help answer questions
- Allow for multiple hours to assemble. Don't leave this for Christmas Eve assembly! I had at least 4 hours into this project.
- Self adhesive 'tap' lights work well with the kitchen to brighten it up.

title: Almost 5 stars

title: Good kitchen, but not as pictured
text:
I bought this kitchen in 2013 and again now. No real complaints about the 2013 purchase aside from it being time consuming to assemble. It was sturdy and survived a lot of play, but it was dirty and had been drawn on with Sharpie and I decided to replace it rather than move it to another house.

The kitchen I got today is not the same one pictured for sale. The pegs are no longer part of it, nor is the shelf in the dishwasher section. The pole on the right side is a thin plastic. Could have sworn that the old one was metal but KidKraft insists they only use wood and plastic. At any rate, it‚Äôs thin, poor quality plastic.

Neither KidKraft nor Amazon could tell me why the kitchen I got is not the same as the kitchen pictured (both websites have the same picture). I suppose they changed the design and didn‚Äôt bother to change anything else. KidKraft‚Äôs answer was maybe Amazon had old stock but that seems unlikely since the old one i has was the one pictured. To their credit, Amazon gave me a partial discount. I certainly wasn‚Äôt going to disassemble and pack it up and ship it back (plus the puppy had already started chewing on the box).

Overall it‚Äôs a good kitchen. This one was easier to assemble than the old one. It‚Äôs only screws, no hex bolts and took about 1.5 hours. Just be aware that you might not get what you expect if you order this.

title: Beautiful toy. A pain to assemble.
text:
I assembled this myself, which took 4+ hours, but I'm not a very "handy" mom. The instructions were good, not great. Most of the steps required 3-4 things to be assembled. In the step where you attach the counter top to the base, make sure you insert the long screws (the ones that have another piece attach to them, which you turn halfway to lock) BEFORE you screw the right side of the sink down to the base on the right side of the oven. The instructions weren't clear on this order, so I ended up not being able to use those long screws. I would have had to unscrew several pieces and retrace my steps, which I wasn't willing to do at that point. I don't think it makes a huge difference, but I can't pick the kitchen up by the counter, or it comes loose.

Once assembled, the kitchen is gorgeous. My 2 yo has fun playing with it. The doors are a little flimsy. Hoping they'll hold up to wear and tear over time.

title: Love this kitchen!
text: I am so happy I shopped around and ended up buying this kitchen for my 2 year old.  It is so nice looking that I don't mind it being in my dining room because the colors match our furniture!  It did take a few hours for assembly, but worth it in the end.  This is a nice size for my daughter now and for her to grow into.  What I probably love most is the amount of storage space.  Other kitchens have rather small spaces for the ovens, fridge, etc.  This easily fits her Melissa and Doug cookie sheets and cupcakes, and stores all of her food, pots and pans, dishes, with room for more!  Toaster or coffee sets, etc. could easily be stored as well.  I also really like that there is a bit of counter space since my daughter will use that to assemble her play, few other sets have this.  The counter space being even a little longer would have been nice.  The paper towel holder can actually hold paper towels.  I bought the Kidkraft Metal Acessories set (pots and pans) to go with it and highly recommend those as well.  Very realistic looking and fit perfect on the burners.  They can also hang from the back splash pegs (although the pans are a little too long to hang, but can still place them there).  Also happy with purchase of Kidkraft plastic dish set.  I think I love this kitchen as much as my daughter does!

We had a plastic Fisherprice kitchen before but my almost three year old was growing out of it and needed something with more room to store her food and more realistic looking. This is PERFECT! I do want to say though it does take a pretty hefty time assembling BUT, it is WELL WORTH IT! It took my husband and I about 5 hours to put together but, that is because we were interrupted a few times by our two daughters and we also wanted to take our time and put it together as perfect as possible. This kitchen is the best kitchen I have come across and for a decent price for how well it is made! It is very sturdy and looks so adorable in our living room, it looks very realistic. It is very roomy, so your children will have plenty of room to store their food and kitchen essentials! My daughters love it! They play with it every day!  The height is perfect for my almost three year old daughter and my one year old has no problem either Cheffing' it up in the kitchen [she can't reach the shelf above the microwave but, that just gives her something to explore when she gets a bit taller!] I can see them having this kitchen for years to come with how well the construction is made and also the height of the kitchen is tall enough for them to grow into as well. title: Great Mini Kitchen
text:
We purchased the KidKraft Uptown kitchen as a Christmas present for my daughter. We had read some reviews about the amount of time that it took to put this baby together so my husband decided to start building it about a week before x-mas eve. My husband is not the best at putting things together so we thought he should get a head start. Much to our surprise it only took him two evenings (about an hour and a half each day) to put the thing together. It seems arranging and laying all of the parts out is key and perhaps the most time consuming part.

The kitchen is so darn cute, very modern looking. My daughter is a tall two year old and has trouble reaching the microwave, but that just means she'll have more things to explore as she gets older. The doors are a little hard to open for her so we usually leave them closed, but not latched (or whatever it is that happens when they close). I wish the burners and faucet made noises simulating the real deal, perhaps that's something the manufacturers could think about. For now imagination will have to do. Other than that, it is a very well designed and built kitchen.

title: Fabulous little kitchen!
text:
I agonized over which kitchen to get for my 3.5 and 5.5 year old daughters and finally settled on this one based on looks, height, and the other reviews I'd read. It came very quickly and in much smaller box than I expected (we were actually able to slide it under the bed to hide it until we assembled it). From unpacking to clean-up, it took exactly 3 hours for my husband and I to assemble. We probably could have done it faster, but are pretty meticulous about organizing our parts, tools, and hardware before we start a project like this. The assembly diagrams were actually pretty clear, although in a few places, we had to look ahead a few steps in order to see what direction a piece was supposed to be turned. During assembly, there were a few times where we thought that something wasn't lining up correctly, but when we continued with the steps and tightened everything down according to directions, everything came into place.

The kitchen is large enough that my 5.5 year old can enjoy it and I'm not worried she's going to out grow it at any moment. All of the Melissa and Doug toys we have fit with the set (for example, our cookie tray fits in the oven). And as for my 3.5 year old... let's just say that if I have to eat any more play spaghetti, soup, or pizza, I'll have a stomach ache. :)

title: Best Kitchen, Once it's Built!
text:
This kitchen is great...once it's assembled. I bought this for my daughter's first birthday and while it was still a little too advanced for her, she did enjoy opening the doors and pulling herself up by the handles. It's seven months later and she LOVES her kitchen. It provides hours of play time for her, which let's face it, is great for me. üòÇ
The refrigerator, freezer, microwave, oven and dishwasher can all be opened and has shelves that can store other toys/play food. This was a huge bonus for us, it actually holds a ton of things and acts like a toy chest at the end of the day. The knobs for the stove and oven can all be turned, as can the faucet. There are some non functioning stickers but way less than they typical play kitchen - but there is a price to pay for that, and we will talk about it in a second. The phone can be taken off the hook, there are knobs on the backsplash to hold utensils, a functioning towel rack, shelf, and chalkboard. All things my toddler loves to use.
My only complaint about this kitchen is it takes FOR-EV-ER to build. All the pros about this kitchen make is a slight con while building it. There are 9 billion pieces and nothing is preassembled. It's not difficult to build, it's just annoying to build.

title: Big assembly project!
text:
The kitchen is nice and my daughter loves it. It is very sturdy and looks great. That is the good news. The bad news: huge assembly nightmare. It took me and my 17 year old son over 5 hours to assemble this, that is 4 hours too many. We were tired and bleary eyed by the time we finished on Christmas Eve. The other bad news: it was missing a burner, so that is a pretty obvious omission. I had a hard time getting through to customer service this morning, so I left them a voice message and sent them an email. So, hopefully they will send that part soon.
For the amount of assembly that is customer required, it should be a lot cheaper. I looked at the assembly instructions online and they had 1/3 less parts that need to be assembled than the assembly instructions that came with our kitchen, For instance, the stove top comes in one pre-assembled piece, whereas our package had approximately 20 pieces to add to the stove top. Way too many big and little pieces and parts to put together! The other negative: this kitchen comes with nothing- not one pot, not one item of food, not even a little oven mitt. I had to buy everything extra. Buyer be very aware!

title: Sturdy, Beautiful Toy Kitchen
text:
We bought this kitchen for my daughter two and a half years ago and it is holding up extremely well.

She was two when she received it and could play with it nicely and reach everything but the tippy top. She is now four and a half and still plays with it. It's still sized appropriately and I don't see her outgrowing it any time soon.

It's very sturdy and I love the colors. The knobs clack when you turn them which is a nice touch. She enjoys writing on the blackboard. The pegs are handy for hanging items onto. I like the fact that there is a refrigerator and freezer section, and believe me, she shelves her food accordingly! The burners are raised which i like. She has always loved the phone, the knob for the faucet turns, she love using the microwave and oven. The rod on the side comes in handy for hanging her dish towels on.

Over all this is a great set in a good price range. I agonized over this decision and am pleased we choose the KidKraft brand.

I will say she is not rough with her toys, but her younger brother is, but nothing has been broken and it seems to be indestructible!

It went together easily and did not take very long at all. Originally we thought the microwave door was not included and so I called Kidkraft and they shipped another one, pronto. We did find out that my husband had just misplaced it and it wasn't actually missing but I was very impressed with KidKraft's customer service.

title: Fabulous Kitchen/Questionable Pieces
text:
I researched for quite a while looking for a kitchen that would not become junk in a few months. I needed something sturdy, streamline (as we have a tiny place), and complete (everything a real kitchen would have.) I feel like that is exactly what we got! We are very happy with the kitchen itself. For that, we would have given 5 stars!
However, we are taking two stars for poor (and luckily for us on this christmas eve, fairly easily remedied) craftsmanship in some of the pieces and bad packaging. The box was barely holding together by the time it got to our home, but luckily, none of the pieces had escaped. One MAIN STRUCTURAL pieces was missing predrilled holes, so with fingers crossed and breathe held, we screwed directly into the piece hoping it wouldn't crack. We will see if it holds up. A few pieces were scratched and the towel bar holes are too large to secure the towel bar from being removed (maybe this is intentional).
Assembly did take a really long time. My husband spent about 4 hours putting it together. However, the many many pieces are clearly labeled and the directions fairly easy to follow (if you can assemble an IKEA piece, you got this!)
All in all, I am delighted with our purchase and look forward to seeing the look on our 3 year old's face when he sees it! I suppose the 4 hour assembly is our baptism by fire into the whole santa thing! ;)

title: Lots of Reasons to Get This Kitchen!
text:
I bought this kitchen set for my daughter. I liked the colors were unisex and it matched our real kitchen. My husband and I put it together one afternoon. We are very experienced in to putting together furniture like the ones from IKEA. This kitchen set took us about 4 hours to put together because of the many parts. It wasn't hard but took a lot of time. First thing that we did that helped was put the parts in number order so it's all easy to find. We noticed that some pieces were scuffed or scratched up. I emailed the customer service and they quickly responded and delivered out the top shelf right away for free. (there were a couple other scratched parts but I didn't care to replace those since they were not as visible than the top piece.)

My one year old daughter loves this kitchen and visits it frequently through out the day. All she really does right now is take play food, utensils and plates (not included) out of the sink but she likes to stand up by it. I think later on, she will play more with the knobs and the cabinets.

My friends and relatives who have older preschool aged kids LOVED this kitchen that a couple of them bought it for their kids because the kids enjoyed playing with it at our home.

It's a good size, not too big or too small. It's sturdy so if a child is using it to stand up, it won't topple over. It's got nice, neutral colorings. It is good for kids of different ages. Can't wait for my daughter to get older and really start playing with it.

title: All the worst of IKEA with none of the rewards.
text:
I'll make this as clear as I can ... DO NOT BUY ANYTHING FROM BY KIDKRAFT

Their products (I have 2 of them now) come with nearly useless instructions. There are no words, just black and white pictures. You have to guess which way is which, often times by counting the visible holes and trying to eyeball which way is up based on alignment. Furthermore, the pictures sometimes show multiple steps in one picture, there is no way to tell which step needs to be done first. Then there are other pictures in which there is only 1 thing to do shown. This should be broken up much better, it would make things (marginally) easier to read.

The various hardware pieces are nearly identical at times, leading to issues where you can't tell which piece is needed where. At least they are sealed in their own individual compartments, so it should be easy to keep things separate. But you can't! Why? Because opening one section means accidentally tearing open the neighboring section and the pieces all mix together.

This company is also one of those places that (for reasons unknown to anyone with basic logic skills) provides no extra pieces for the small, easily lost and/or destroyed pieces but a few extras for the bigger, stronger pieces. This means you'll invariably reach a point where you either are missing something critical that can't be replaced with a trip to Home Depot or left with extra parts and confused what you forgot to do. It is a maddening process.
