text: Love this kitchen, but as a 71 year old grandmother, it took me all of 8 hours to build it by myself. It took a good 45 minutes to carefully disassemble the box and lay out all the forty plus parts in order and peruse the pictorial directions. Before purchasing I read many of the reviews about assembly and they were very helpful when I put the kitchen together‚Äîhints about being careful to use the proper screw colors on the brown and silver pieces, etc. I  would add, if you don‚Äôt have a helper to hold parts in place, try using blue painter‚Äôs tape to hold parts steady. I also had a bar of soap handy to lubricate the screws if they did not go into the wood easily. In addition to the tiny wrench and the Allen wrench that comes with the kitchen, you only need a Phillips head screw driver. It was a labor of love to put this kitchen together. I am now saving Green Giant vegetable and small frozen pizza boxes to stock the freezer, also milk and butter cartons for the fridge. You can loosely fill them with small bunches of paper towels or aluminum foil and tape shut to keep their shape.  Went to the dollar store and got a small timer and and some wire baskets that look kind of like dishwasher racks for dishwasher. I purchased the KidKraft pots and pans which fit perfectly on the burners. Also purchased the Melissa and Doug slice and bake cookies and cookie sheet for the oven.

title: Best kid's kitchen! Looks beautiful in the playroom.
text:
This is actually the second time we've purchased and put together this kitchen, because we love it so much. We donated the first one to a friend. He's a very tall almost-five-year-old, and he still adores it. You would expect most kids to have outgrown a pretend kitchen by now, but he still loves it. It looks like a real kitchen, so he feels like he's getting to be a grown up when he serves us pretend food! This is, hands down, the best kid's kitchen ever. Solid wood. Easy instructions. Although it takes a while to assemble, it's worth every minute. It's such a wonderful addition to my son's playroom! It looks so much nicer than the plastic ones, and my son loves that is has all the parts of a real kitchen.

My one complain is that my son was so excited to have it put together and get to play with it that we went ahead with the assembly even after noticing that the "new" kitchen had several parts with scratches. One of the screws packets was taped up, which makes me think that we did not receive a new item. The phone had scratches. The sink had scratches. I'm hoping they'll send some replacement parts since I was under the assumption we were receiving a new product. The scratch on the phone upset my son a bit, but the scratches elsewhere were pretty irrelevant. Just disappointing when you think you're getting a new item. Will keep you all posted!

title: Excellent Design and Assembly Instructions
text: I have built many products over the years that come disassembled, tightly packed in cardboard boxes, that weigh quite a bit. This unit weighed in at about 70 pounds. It took me about 2 1/2 hours to assemble, and I was amazed at how well the components were labelled, made, and most importantly, fit together. Without a doubt, this was the best designed partical board kit I have ever built. The instructions were spot on even though there were primarily only pictures to follow. Kidkraft really did an outstanding job numbering parts and coordinating them with the assembly instructions. Kidkraft suggests that you do NOT use a power drill/screwdriver to assemble this. I did. If you set the clutch on the driver to its lowest setting it will drive all the fasteners home with just the right amount of torque. Some of the smaller screws that attach to the ends of boards should be done by hand, however, even if one does strip, this kit is designed so that most every component has multiple fasteners holding it in place. After I finished this there wasn't a single door out of alignment, they all shut and latched securely and properly. This is a very well designed childs toy. Be patient assembling it and you will be well rewarded. I do wish that they provided some sort of battery system that could be used to create lighting and additional sounds for some of the components. They are not really needed though........my granddaughter makes her own noises. They would mostly be for my enjoyment!

I didn't give this 5 stars, only because it was a lot of work to put this together. Literally no part of this kitchen came assembled. But it turned out to be a fun project for my husband and I. If you are concerned with putting together a kitchen, don't be. Each piece was numbered, including all the nuts and bolts. The instructions were straight forward. Kidkraft did an excellent job with labeling and packaging the pieces.

Once put together, the kitchen is extremely sturdy. I've very impressed with the quality and the attention to detail.

When buying utensils, I caution that you check the size. There isn't a ton a room under the hanging pegs. Also, look for utensils that have large openings for hanging, as the pegs are pretty thick. Most sets we looked at wouldn't work. We just ordered a set, I hope it works.

We will be having fun with this kitchen for a long time to come.

title: Some good, some bad, but still a good kitchen
text:
Got this for my 2yo daughter for Christmas. Took about 2 hours to put together, but that seems reasonable for the number of pieces and connections required.

My complaints:
Instructions/packaging. They have one of those cardboard blister packs with all the hardware many pieces. they didn't label the back with the part number/letter. so i had to keep flipping over to find it. Also they had up to 3 different locations and "types" for a part. one screw (part letter C?) was in 3 spots and they were 3 different screws. well the length and thread were the same, but the head was either metal, white or brown. Looking back, i should have noticed, but at 1am it wasn't my first though. I wish they would have labeled like C.1 for white, C.2 for brown or something. this way you know to grab the brown screw for securing a brown wood piece, etc. since most of the screws will be hidden by the location of them and the position of the toy it isn't as bad. but still, a little ocd gets me when i see a stainless head on the brown backing.

also, the foam packing is a pain to clean. it gets all static charged up and sticks and is a pain to clean. expect to be finding pieces of white foam for months, unless you take your time and deconstruct everything. i suggest building in a VERY open space. this will allow for cleaning of the parts, and being able to spread them out and easily identify what pieces are which and what goes next.

as for durability, it has been holding up. Had a play-date a few days ago and 5 2yos were using and nothing broke. I'll wait and see.

but it seems like a pretty good deal.

title: Know what you're getting into...

title: Poor quality
text:
To begin, this is an adorable kitchen. The size is perfect (I can see my daughter playing with it for years to come), it fits Melissa & Doug food toys, it looks great and my 23 month old daughter absolutely loves it. It also wasn't challenging to put together.

However, the quality of the kitchen is poor. Straight out of the box: 1) the dishwasher painting was already partially scraped off. 2) the microwave door does not align properly, thus the microwave door does not close properly 3) the dishtowel dowel doesn't even fit through the pre-drill holes on the towel rack 4)there were several dents on the kitchen handles and chipped paint. On top of this, I also purchased the Kid Kraft metal accessories set only to find the spaghetti pot dented in several locations at the bottom sides.

I did call Kid Kraft customer service. They are sending me out new parts of all that I mentioned above, no hesitations or questions asked (makes me wonder if this happens frequently with their products).

I'm not sure if it's just my luck that I got such a lemon of their products or if this is a usual habit of this company. Just wanted to give a warning. With all this trouble, my daugher and I still really like this kitchen. There isn't anything else out there like it except the super expensive Pottery Barn one.

Anyways, assembly sucked. We won't be getting a divorce but may need a counselor. The pay off was huge to see my daughter play with it. It is a little tall for her but she will be able to grow into it. I will be interested to see how long it lasts, it's put together by press board and plastic hinges, so who knows. This in not for a rookie assembler, it takes a while, there are 32 steps and can get overwhelming.

This only gets 4 stars because my daughter loves it, it seems like it's ok quality for what we paid for it, unsure about longevity. Good luck and if you get stuck search kidkraft kitchen assembly in YouTube.

text:

Once together it makes for a durable, seemingly well-made play kitchen for your kid(s). I have moved this around the house a few times, and have had no issues with it coming apart or anything. You will also find that many people that have purchased this or similar items like to customize them by adding lighting and all sorts of stuff to the final design and set up.

This item is not only cheaper but higher quality (yes I know those two things usually don't go well together) than comparable items you may find in your big box stores. I was initially skeptical because I had never heard of this brand, but after reading reviews decided to give it a try.

I believe this was eligible for PRIME shipping, so it came quickly. The box was a bit beat up from shipping but everything inside was intact and how it was supposed to be.

I would absolutely purchase this item again, and recommend anyone that is looking for a play kitchen to do the same.

title: Good product but a few minor assembly annoyances
text:
First off, this thing is solid and looks great. I may be proven wrong by my kids, but this feels like it will last. I only deducted two stars because of to issues I had in assembly (note, assembly to me about 3 hours, including a short dinner break).

I deducted one star because while the hardware package does a great job at identifying which bolts are A, E, or other letters in the instructions, there are two colors of bolts. The brown bolts should be used on the exterior and the silver bolts should be used on interior faces. This could be remedied by either giving different colors of the same bolt spec different letters (so you only use the silver on the interior faces) or by making all bolts brown. As a result, I got to the end and have five silver bolt heads exposed on a brown panel.

I subtracted a second star because the poor quality of the bolts caused one to break during assembly. I had to use a cutoff wheel and screwdriver to extract the broken screw, adding 10 minutes to my install time. If I didn't own a Dremel this would not have been possible to fix.

If Kidkraft fixes these two problems with their fasteners this will solidly be a five star product.

title: Amazing children's kitchen!!
text: We bought this kitchen for my 18 month old son who is obsessed with cooking.  He takes all my pots and pans and tries to turn on my stove! So we thought that buying him his own kitchen would be a good investment. This turned out to be one of the best purchases we've made!! The kitchen is beautiful (much nicer than mine!) and very sturdy.  There is plenty of storage space to hold all his kitchen equipment - toy food, pots, pans etc. in the stove, fridge, freezer or dishwasher.  I love how real this kitchen looks - the appliances are all "stainless steel" with a "granite" counter.  This piece was designed very well with a lot of attention to detail.  There is a towel rack on the side, and hooks to hang utensils on behind the stove.  My baby loves to turn the burners and wash dishes in his sink.  This kitchen occupies him all day! He still likes to steal my pots though :)  I highly recommend this kitchen - especially for the low price offered on Amazon! The only downside I can think of is that it took my husband about 5 hours to assemble (but he's not really the handy type).  The instructions were easy to follow, just time-consuming.  Other people mentioned some parts arriving damaged, but we didn't have any issues.  All in all, we are extremely pleased with this well-made product!

title: Quality, Worth the Time
text:
I knew going in based on other reviews it would take awhile to assemble, but I did not anticipate that it would take 4 hours. This was only in small part to my kitchen-building partner who was getting progressively drunk as the night wore on, but still. This is NOT a fast build. Truly be warned.

HOWEVER, the quality of the product is outstanding and I can tell it will last for quite awhile. There is a good amount of space to store things like food, pots, pans, dishes, etc. Another note in other reviews was that it was a bit taller than other play kitchens (which was preferred for us because our 3 year old is considerably taller than other toddlers and his baby brother is looking like he'll match that height in the coming years), and that held true. It's a great height now and looks like it will continue to be accommodating for a bit. It also looks great with our adult furniture, which seems a silly thing to worry about, but in our current living situation makes me very happy.

Most importantly, my son loves it. He thought the phone feature was particularly fun so he can "call" Grandma and tell her all about the soup he's cooking, haha!

title: Top Notch and Tons of Fun!
text:
Purchased this for my 2.5 year old daughter and as a toy my infant son can also grow to enjoy.

I love that it is gender neutral and matches the decor of my home. It is currently set up in my kitchen and my daughter loves to cook in it while I cook. The height of the kitchen is perfect as nothing is too tall for my daughter right now and a 7 year old cousin has also been able to use it with ease. This shows me that the kitchen will provide hours of fun far into the future.

The only troublesome thing about this kitchen is that it will take some effort to put together. In fact, I could tell that the kitchen we received had previously been returned. It seemed someone opened it and found all the pieces too daunting and took it back. Still, the kitchen we received had all the pieces and the directions were easy to follow. In my opinion, four hours of installation is nothing for the countless hours of fun this activity center will provide.

Other notes about the kitchen:
It is visually stunning and I get compliments on it whenever someone visits.

The lack of lights and electronic features could be a con for some people, but I feel it encourages my daughter to use her own imagination.

The lack of bright colors could also be seen as a con, but I think that the fact that her kitchen looks like mine makes her feel more engrossed in her imaginative play as she models what she sees "mommy" doing (and discourages her from trying to play with my ice maker and dishwasher since she has one of her own!)

Overall, if you are considering this kitchen it is probably because of the contemporary look and the fact that it is made of wood and not clunky plastic. Though I have only owned it for about three months, so far I can say the quality matches the look and we aren't missing the bells and whistles of another kitchen. Go for it and enjoy watching your child explore the culinary world!

title: This review is based soley on assembly time and not ...
text: This review is based soley on assembly time and not the quality of the product. If you have ordered this kitchen for Christmas be sure you put it together ASAP, as you are not going to want to spend a very large portion of your Christmas Eve or Christmas Day putting it together. My husband spent nearly 6 hours assembling this kitchen, with my help here and there. He said it was one of the most time consuming and elaborate things he has EVER put together (including adult furniture). Although the procedure is not difficult, it takes a very long time and in hindsight if we worked together it probably would have cut an hour or two off the process. My husband noted that he didn't know why more of the parts didn't come pre-assembled. For example, knobs, door handles, and grills could have come attached already. You literally have to put every single thing together. It is an awful lot of work for a kids toy. If your little boy or girl is the kind of kid who plays with something for a few days and is over it, then this kitchen is NOT worth the effort.

title: Looks great but...
text:
I've been shopping around for a kitchen set for my 4 1/2 year old boy/girl twins who both love to play "kitchen" at preschool. I loved the look of this kitchen but, was concerned by some of the comments indicating that, upon opening the box, pieces were damaged, missing or flat out broken. I opted to take the plunge after several reviewers described positive experiences with KidKraft customer service re: replacement of damaged/broken pieces. I was very worried when our package arrived looking as though it had been dragged behind the UPS truck down a gravel road. The box was literally on the verge of tearing open when we brought it into the house. Happily, however, none of the pieces were broken or damaged!

Other reviewers' posts about assembly time are accurate. Putting this thing together is not trivial. I would estimate it took my husband the better part of three hours to get it fully assembled. He did have two "helpers" who may have slowed things down a bit, but, regardless, I recommend not waiting until the night before/morning of a birthday or holiday to open the box and start assembling.

Overall, we're quite pleased with our purchase. If I had one quibble it would be that the doors seem difficult for my kids to open-they really have to tug on the handle and then close it quite forcefully. We'll see how long those handles remain attached and whether or not the latches on the door continue to work.

title: 4 hours 10 minutes to put together by skilled carpenter
text:
I gave this kitchen a 5 star review because now that it's built, it looks adorable and my 2 year old and 7 year old, absolutely love it. I will caution that a friend of our family put it together, and he noticed some pieces had been drilled upside down, and at least 3 major wood pieces did not fit. Given his skill level in carpentry, however (he builds custom wood projects for others, as a side business), he was easily able to disassemble the factory components, line things up correctly and he had to drill some new holes. He also noted that 2 of the external brown colored screws were not included, so, he used silver ones. It looks alright to us. He also cautioned that the top piece that goes along the top of the microwave, is not flush with the back of the unit, another factory error that required his ingenuity to get past. So if this is a Christmas surprise, do not wait until Christmas Eve to build it!! It took him
4 hours and 10 minutes (including about 15 minutes of that timeframe to eat dinner with our family - it was the least we could do, right?!) ... Even if you think you're pretty skilled, I'm certain you'll find this kitchen a challenge to assemble. The only difference I noticed from the picture, is the phone. We received a wooden one that appears "digital" like a cell phone. It doesn't have large numbers like the one shown. That was a little disappointing, because my 2 year old is learning to recognize written numbers. Oh well. So glad this was on sale, I wouldn't pay over $112 for this kitchen. Some wood pieces were scratched too, but a brown sharpie marker fixed it. Honestly, the little dings, and bumps along the way trying to assemble it don't really matter once it's together. It still looks really cute and my girls love it, so 5 stars it is. I'm also ok with it in our family room because it's not an eye sore like some of the other toy kitchens out there. It's also compact and doesn't take up too much space, but still has an oven large enough for them to put toy cookie trays, etc., inside, for more realistic dramatic play. ... We bought the matching laundry unit with a washer/dryer, but that will have to be assembled at a later date. I peeked in the box though and it matches this kitchen perfectly! Both are "espresso".

title: Takes lots of effort to assemble, but high quality
text:
To be assembled this kitchen requires the patience of a Tibetan monk, the cunning of Machiavelli and the tenacity of a 4 year old begging for dessert. My husband and I are not stupid, I have a doctorate, and he is an engineer... And it took the two if us about 4 hours to put this together. And maybe 1 extra hour dedicated to swearing at it. It was tedious, the directions were pictures and it required us to assemble everything (as in installing the door catches, adding all of the knobs on the stove, the door handles.
Nothing is pre assembled.

On the other hand, this kitchen is solid. It is very high quality, and if not such a pain to assemble would be worth much more than it sells for. I feel like I could jump on it and it would probably be fine. It is very handsome and well designed.
We have 3 small and squirrelly children that take great delight in destroying things, and I doubt that they can take this thing out. I never say never, but this is a pretty formidable kitchen.

The finishing is nice; when we assembled it we assembled it partially on tile flooring and it definitely got kicked around (and cursed at!) but you'd never know it. Our toddler has hit it with wild abandon and a rather sturdy set of wooden pots. Still looking excellent several months later!

I also appreciate that they even considered air holes in the oven/dishwasher compartments. Or toddler thinks its hilarious to close himself in there, so it could have been a really bad situation.

When you assemble this bad boy, I recommend laying our several sheets of paper and carefully marking and dividing all of the screws, etc. you'll thank yourself later, trust me.

title: Love this kitchen set
text: Love this kitchen set!  Its really high quality, and very solidly built.  And for the 10,000 screws and things needed to put this together, everything lined up perfectly.  One reviewer commented that this kitchen is constructed better than a lot of furniture, and having assembled tons of furniture, grills, etc in the past, I would have to agree with that statement.  I put this together myself over the span of two evenings.  It took 2 -3 hours to do with nothing more than a Philips head screwdriver and the allen wrench that came with the hardware.  My one bit of advice would be this: the wood panel between the oven and the dishwasher has plastic strips on both sides of it.  This is where the oven and dishwasher racks slide in and out.  There is only one screw to attach the two plastic strips to the wood.  In other words, you screw through a piece of plastic, a piece of wood, and then another piece of plastic with one Philips head screw.  I completely stripped the head of the screw trying to get it in.  Drill through both pieces of plastic before putting the screws in so that they go in a little easier.  I ended up having to hunt through my tool box to find a replacement screw; it was a tiny bit longer than the one that came with the kitchen and now the oven rack is hard to get in and out because it rubs against the screw.  Overall, this was a small issue.  I highly recommend this purchase.

title: I'd give ten stars if I could for this KidKraft kitchen.
text: This play kitchen exceeds all expectations.  The quality of the product is truly second to none and the packaging was neatly organized and user friendly.  It took 4 hours to assemble, but not beause it was a difficult assembly.  I'm meticulous and really took my time to be sure I did it properly.  The instructions were incredibly well explained, every single piece was carefully numbered and the hardware blister pack was neatly organized and labeled.  I was very impressed with the quality of the hardware too.  Oftentimes products like these will provide cheap hardware, such as soft screws that strip the moment you tighten them.  Not this hardware.  Not at all.  My 2 year old daughter received this as her birthday gift and she absolutely loves it!  She proudly talks about "her kitchen" and has played with it non stop since she received it.  I highly recommend this kitchen to anyone who, like me, is particular about the look of a gigantic toy that will be a centerpiece of your living space.  It is absolutely adorable, not only looks quality but IS quality, and I believe will stand the test of time with several years of constant play.

I give it four stars, because while the quality is great, it's time consuming to assemble.  I assembled it on my own, and it took just under 4 hours.  The instructions just have pictures of what goes where, in what order, and what to use, which at times made it difficult.  I appreciated that everything did have a number sticker on it, so it was easy to identify each piece. I also made a few mistakes, which added to the assembly time, since I had to figure out how to correct it without completely undoing all the work I'd done, but once the assembly was done, I'm very happy with it. One suggestion for the manufacturer would be to add some written tips or instructions in addition to the pictures.

title: Excellent but difficult to build
text:
I agree with many of the other reviewers - this is an excellent play kitchen. It's sturdy, high quality, and very nice to look at. I was just amazed at how complicated it was to put together! My father-in-law assisted me - and he's a very handy guy - and it took us about 4 and a half hours. We were stuck at the very first step in the instructions for 30-40 minutes, just staring confusedly at the diagram. There are 35 steps, but each step really contains 4-10 sub-steps. They really should have broken things up a bit more to reduce confusion. Though some other posters have boasted about putting it together quickly and/or by themselves, I would recommend having a helper. Some of the steps are a little tricky for a not-particularly-handy dad like me.

Be aware that it doesn't come with anything besides the kitchen itself. That's not a negative - just be aware. You'll need to purchase play food, pots/pans, etc. separately. That said, my 2 and a half year old is much more interested in the cordless phone part of it rather than the kitchen itself, at least right now.

So if you're looking for a good non-plastic play kitchen with a dark wood/stainless steel look, this is the one. Just be prepared to spend a good amount of time putting it together. But when you're done, sit back with pride and hope that your child will appreciate the effort you put, at least implicitly by actually playing with it!

title: Very Nice Kitchen and It Was As Expected.
text:
Bought this as a gift from Santa for my daughter. Started assembly yesterday. Haven't completed it yet as my 4 year old daughter can't seem to stay out of the house long enough. I may change some things with the review once it is completed.
PROS; 1: Firstly, I inventoried all the items and everything was there.I was definitely worried about missing parts as described in other reviews. Luckily, mine came complete. 2: Firm construction, thought I was putting together an actually piece of furniture with the type of hardware that comes with the kitchen. 3: Aesthetic, I showed my wife what it looked like this far. We are very pleased with how it looks.
CONS; 1: So far, the instructions for assembly have been easy to follow with the exception of one task that was a "light bulb" moment. I'll update with pictures when the project is completed. This portion should be two separate steps. 2: I would like to see the colored (brown/stainless) hardware separated as during assembly, questioning which to use was frustrating. I'll explain more with pictures. 3: If you want to complete the assembly in one sitting, ensure you do set aside 2.5 hours. Several small parts to assemble like the clasps that hold each door closed, the handles, knobs, etc. 4: Do not over tighten screws, especially the small ones. 5: If the "light bulb" moment mentioned above would have been two steps, I would have avoided breaking a screw into the bottom of the cylindrical part, which in the main picture appears to be chrome on the right side. 5: Now that I have looked again, the faucet appears chrome in the picture. Nothing has that appearance. It is all flat grey with a "silver" shine.
RECOMMENDATION; I would recommend this kitchen to a friend and family member. I do feel the quality is very good and I believe this kitchen will last for quite some time even with my daughter's waking path of destruction. I'd give 5 stars if they made changes as I mentioned above and make the "chrome" looking items appear how they come.
EDIT: Before and after step 22, assembly was easy. Step 22 should be separated into different steps as you have to 'undo' if you placed board 21 onto the assembly first as I did. In order to screw the 'pole' #20 onto the 'board' #21, you have to have access to the recessed portion on the bottom as the head of the screw sits there. Putting together the 'pole' and faucet should come first. Other than that and the appearance of chrome, I like it.

title: Expresso Kitchen Assembly Tips and Review
text: The build quality of this Kitchen exceeds all assemble yourself furniture I have bought over the years from Wallmart, Target and Ikea. I was impressed how well all the holes lined up. The furniture is very sturdy if properly assembled. Some tips for assembly are: Step 22, there are four "Q" screws to install in this step, even though the diagram shows two. For the expresso-colored kitchen, both "A" and "C" screws come in two colors: silver and brown, which is a great touch. Choose the color that best matches the furniture color in the parts that are visible. For example, for step 15 use the brown-colored "C" screws; for Step 16, use the silver-colored "A" screws since this area is not visible; for step 22 use the silver colored "C" screw, ... It does take some time to assemble it, but it is totally worth it. It took me 3 hours and 45 minutes to complete the project. My daughter absolutely loved it!

title: Great looking, quality toy kitchen
text:
We purchased this kitchen for Christmas this year and I can't say enough good things about it. First off it is adorable and of good quality. It is one of the best looking toy kitchens I have ever seen (maybe second to buying all the expensive Pottery Barn sets) which I considered. However it is a great value compared to that as really almost as attractive. Love that it has four burners, a dishwasher and microwave, chalk board, phone and removable cutting board in the dishwasher. The dials/knobs on the stove make clicking noises when they are turned. Also-the kitchen provides more than ample storage space for all of her toy foods and small appliance and dishware etc. plus it still has room to spare for other toy storage as well. It is a good height for her to play with and looks like it will still be appropriately sized for a few more years. She seems to really love her kitchen and plays quietly with it all the time which is great!
We also go the Melissa a Doug cookie set and it fits in the oven as well. Honestly I can't say enough great things about this product-- don't hesitate to purchase this item. Finally- in our experience assembling this it was time consuming (about 2 hours) however it was easy. The directions were good there were just a lot of pieces. I was slightly worried based on other reviewers comments that we would find out it was missing parts or damaged as we put it together on Christmas Eve but that was not the case at all. The kitchen appears of great quality and all pieces were accounted for.

title: Very good product
text:
We purchased this kitchen for our almost-three-year-old daughter for Christmas, and it was an instant hit. While I can't speak to the durability, since we just bought it, it seems very solid and like it will withstand the wear and tear that comes with toddlers. The actual product is true to the picture; if possible, it looks even nicer in person (my husband and I joked that it's not fair our toddler has a nicer kitchen than we do). If you have a small living space, like we do, with no designated play room, this is a great choice because it fits with most decors; it's not cutesy like other toy kitchens.

My daughter loves turning the knobs on the stove and putting things in the oven, dishwasher, sink, fridge and microwave. The phone is a great source of entertainment for her as she's "cooking," and it's great to see her imagination soar as she comes up with different "recipes". She played with it for a good two hours the first day she got it and has been playing with it regularly ever since.

My only slight complaints are as follows:

--It is very time-consuming to put together. My husband started at 10:30 pm and didn't finish it until after 12:30 am (closer to 1 am). And this man is an engineer who is very good at putting things together, so it's not like it was user error. So plan on plenty of time to set this up; don't think you can get up an hour before they do on Christmas morning and have it put together.
--Also, there were some slight nicks in the wood, which was disappointing, but not nearly enough to affect the look of the product or our satisfaction with it. Still, it's annoying that we noticed some nicks there as we took it out of the box (so we know it wasn't our daughter).
--It does show fingerprints easily, which probably wouldn't be too much of an issue for older children, but for toddlers who often have stuff on their hands (despite my best intentions!), the kitchen definitely shows that. But, it just means I'll have to wipe it down more frequently.

All in all, a great buy that will be used by my daughter (and any other future children) for years to come.

One note, though; I got it on Walmart.com for $60 less than the price advertised on Amazon on the day I wrote this review, so that is something to consider, as well.

text:
My son received this as a gift for Christmas. It is sturdy, nice looking, and just as the other reviews say, it takes some time to put together. I did get frustrated because some of the screws are colored brown so that they match the outside and others are silver, however in the packaging they do not divide them up or explain in the instructions.
Also, all the parts that are not wood are plastic, and I am a little worried they will easily brake. If you don't mind putting it together and some plastic, this is perfect! My son loves it, but I am a bit picky, and personally I would have saved up an extra $100 to get an all wooden kitchen that may be a little smaller but would definitely last for generations to come. P.s. He also received the Melissa and Doug pots and pans set, and they are a little too wide for the microwave so they door cannot shut if they are in there. text: I bought it for Christmas for my 3 years old kid. He loves it. I was nervous with some of the reviews saying it takes forever to put it together and all. Here is my two cents about it - I would advice to have two poeple put it together to go faster. First, organize all pieces in the numerical order even the small pieces. Keep the small pieces in their original bags cause the number is on the bag! Tips to open the screws, cut the plastic with a cutter; do not rip it from the back - so you know the number of each screws! Second, have one person hand out the right pieces and screws to the other person putting it together. It took me and my dad 2 hours. There are lots of screws but all worth it cause it seems to be great quality! The instruction could have been better written and drawn at some of the steps; but overall it's okay and use your common sense.  Great result and quality at the end!

title: Try a different brand!
text:
As many other reviewers have stated the assembly of this kitchen can be overwhelming. When I opened the box and removed all the parts I was a bit terrified as to how long this would take to assemble. But having put together many Ikea furniture items in my day, I thought I was up for the task. I got to step 14 (of 32) only to realize that the predrilled holes do not align correctly with the other parts and assembly would be impossible without obtaining a replacement part.
In kidkraft's defense, their customer service was able to order the part for me and they are expediting delivery; however I have no idea if the part will arrive in time for Christmas.
I paid $245 for a kids kitchen and they cannot even drill the holes correctly. Although I ordered the replacement part I'll be returning the item.
Look around at what other brands have to offer, because paying nearly 300 dollars for a kids toy an having it be defective is just plain wrong!

title: Great little kitchen
text:
We bought this kitchen for our 3 year old daughter for Christmas. It comes in a long, flat box. Pretty heavy, not the easiest for one person to move around. One corner of the box was pretty well crushed, but the styrofoam packing inside kept all the pieces unbroken.
Assembly wasn't bad, but you should grab a cordless drill and set aside a couple hours. The instructions are straightforward and all the panels and hardware are numbered, which makes it much easier. I put it together myself, but there were a few steps where another set of hands really would've helped. Most of the hardware was very similar to what you'd find with other furniture you assemble yourself, e.g. the stuff from a certain big Swedish store. If that gives you problems, maybe this kitchen isn't for you.
The only minor issue was that some of the hardware was labeled the same and was essentially identical except for being two different colors - some brown and some stainless steel (see photo). It was unclear in the instructions where each color was meant to go, and I didn't have the patience to try to figure it out myself. Otherwise, this is a great little kitchen.

title: Great kitchen!!! - plus a couple tips for assembly!
text:
I did not realize when I purchased this kitchen it was notably one of the hardest ones to assemble. So thankfully after reading some reviews I knew what my husband and I were getting into. Once assembled it is so dang sturdy and will last forever!

Tips:
- Put this kitchen together with ANOTHER PERSON. My husband was the main assembly person but it would have taken 2x as long if I wasn‚Äôt there to help. We laid everything out and I had the instructions and all the screws + extra parts. So as he was working on the current step I was setting out the things needed for the next step and could just hand it over and tell him what needed done.
- Split up the assembly into 2 parts. For 2 nights we put the kids in bed, put on The Office, and got to work.
- Try to be nice to the other person. Honestly I thought we would fight a bunch during this project, but since we each had a role and we knew we were making this for our kids we didn‚Äôt have a single argument. (There was a moment I was tired and MAYBE got a little sassy but ü§∑üèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è)
- A milkshake run by one of you while the other sets out the pieces is a really good idea!

Anyways I hope this review helps someone! In total it took us 3 1/2 hrs to assemble. That is about 8 episodes on The office. You can do it!

text:
We love, love, love this kitchen set we got our 3 year daughter for Christmas. I did a lot of research and read a ton of reviews, and I‚Äôm very glad we went with this one. The only ‚Äúnegative‚Äù thing that I have to say about it, is it‚Äôs heavy. But that‚Äôs also a positive because it is very sturdy. Our 18 month old loves it too and it keeps them both entertained for very long periods of time. It looks sophisticated and it has very realistic details.
We are chronic procrastinators and waited until Christmas Eve to assemble it, but we (my husband) got it done in less than 2.5 hours. Just follow the directions. Take all the pieces out of the box and take the time to organize everything by their numbers and DON‚ÄôT do it alone. I also HIGHLY recommend having a drill handy with an Allen wrench/Torx bit. title: Stay away unless you think IKEA furniture is fun
text:
The product looks great. It's also nice that it has not flashing lights, beeping sounds, etc., so kids are forced to use their own imagination.

BUT, it takes HOURS to put it together. The directions are clear, but contain 32 steps, and some of the steps combine several sub-steps. There must be at least 20 parts and 70 screws and bolts etc. in the package. You will spend hours assembling it. Moreover, not all holes will lineup properly, especially in the latter stages when many pieces must fit together. Have you ever tried to get a screw into a bolt on an angle? Doesn't work so great.

I am not a great handyman, but I've assembled plenty of IKEA furniture, including our son's crib and changing table. IKEA furniture assembly is nothing compared to this one. So be forewarned!

text: Got this for daughter who is turning two.  It took my husband and me 3 hours to put together. (Note: place brown screws on all outer pieces and the one white painted screw is for the telephone key pad.) We had to guess when to use the painted screws and on our last two steps realized we had guessed wrong with a couple of them.  But it wasn't too difficult to unscrew and re-screw them so all the painted ones were on the outside. It does look nicer to have all the painted screws in the correct places. (Note: brown painted screws should go on all the exposed outside pieces and the one white painted screw is for the telephone key pad.  Some of the painted screws will be used for the interior pieces.) It has been worth all the effort of putting this kitchen together because our daughter loves it and has played with it nonstop for the 2 days she has had it.  We knew she would like it because she plays with the play kitchen in our church nursery every Sunday.  The design is very nice and great for our very tall 2 yr old. title: Best toy kitchen for my needs
text:
I spent a lot of time looking around for a kitchen to buy for my 3 year old daughter. I also have a 9 month old son who will eventually play with this as well, so there were a few things that were extremely important to me in finding the right kitchen:

1. Size. Something substantial enough that they wouldn't grow out of too quickly. Height as well as ability for multiple kids to play was critical. Also needed enough space to actually "play". A lot of the kitchens I saw were small with some burners and a sink but no flat area to "cut" vegetables or place items.

2. Storage. With all of the stuff that comes along with a toy kitchen, it was critical to find something with ample storage. Many kitchens had a lot of little drawers and spaces, but nothing that could even fit the Melissa & Doug cookie set (I read in another review that the toy fit easily in the oven)

3. Gender neutral. Not a deal breaker, but would be nice to have something my son could play with that wasn't pink.

4. Price. Again, not a deal breaker, but who wants to overspend?

Finally, after comparing and looking at the KidKraft Big Kitchen (too pink), KidKraft Vintage Kitchen (way too small), Pottery Barn kitchen (too expensive and too many pieces), KidKraft Grand Gourmet Corner Kitchen (too many small drawers) &Melissa & Doug Classic Kitchen (not bad, was a close second to my purchase, but my husband didn't like the colors) among a few others, we finally chose this one.

First, the assembly. As noted by other reviewers, it's not hard to put together, but is time consuming and I would recommend two adults. Many of the steps could be completed simultaneously if you had 2 screwdrivers and 2 people. Even so, it took us over 2 hours to finish it. The parts mostly aligned with one or two tight squeezes. All of the parts arrived undamaged, although there is a small plastic piece that goes under the knobs that enables the knob to make a clicking noise when you turn it... two of mine broke while installing. I will be calling them for replacement parts. I understand their customer service is great. Make sure not to throw away the instructions for calling customer service that is in the box - it includes a batch number that you will need.

The completed product looks beautiful. It is the small details that makes this so great. The chalkboard on the fridge, the towel holder off of the side and the phone. My daughter had a play date the next day with 3 of her preschool friends all banging the kitchen about and it seemed to hold up just fine. Only time will tell how well the product holds up over the long term, but so far I've been happy with the product. The price point was an added bonus!

title: Durable, Sturdy, Well-Designed
text:
We bought this for our 2 year old daughter.

Assembly does take some time (2.5 hours for me) but the instructions are straight-forward. Each piece is identified with a removable sticker and the screws/washers/fasteners are neatly organized and are identified in a packet. The set comes with a small wrench and Allen wrench, but you will need a screwdriver and a Phillips screwdriver. I recommend a power tool to speed up assembly. The alignment for the board pieces was good, much better than some Ikea furniture pieces I have assembled in the past.

The packet comes with a few spare parts but, in my case, they were not enough. Toward the end of assembly, I noticed two screws were missing. Having read some of the other customer reviews about missing/defective parts, it was disappointing but not a surprise given my tempered expectations. I used one of the spare screws that came with the packet and called the KidKraft customer service line to request the other. A live representative answered the call (a real person!). Without issue, and without any scrutiny, she said she would expedite a replacement packet and it arrived in a couple days. In this respect, the negative is that some pieces were missing and the plus is customer service took care of it quickly.

The kitchen is stable enough that it sits on our carpet without wobble. It's heavy enough that I don't have a high concern that it can be knocked over during use, but it's light enough that my wife or I can move/drag it to a different location without much difficulty.

The latches are tight so our daughter needs help opening the doors. I figure that that as she gets stronger and as the latches get more use, they will loosen and the doors will be easier to open.

She can't reach the top shelf, "microwave," or "freezer" yet but she'll grow into it. Our daughter's three year old and four year old cousins and friends can reach them easily.

She's filled the cupboards with toy foods and uses wooden Melissa and Doug pots and pans. The M&D pots/pans aren't fully compatible in that you can't hang them on the knobs on the kitchen, but they look scaled to the stove top. There is plenty of storage space but very little counter top (a rounded area to the right of the sink, that's it).

The knobs for the stove and faucet click and turn but there are no push-button sounds or automated elements (as advertised). The stove top elements are plastic. The sink basin is removable and plastic, making for easy cleaning.

title: Very good quality product.
text: Very good quality product.  I have bought many items that have needed to be put together and I was impressed with this item.  It seems a little smaller than it appears in the picture, but my grand daughter is a little peanut, so I was actually relieved that it wasn't bigger.  Takes about 3 hours to put together with power screw driver and a phillips and hex tip.  I am pretty handy and enjoy putting things together.  Follow the instructions, don't try to set any assembly records and you shouldn't have any trouble. There are a couple of ambiguous directions, look at the way the door hinges work and you should be able to figure it out.  There are a lot of silver and brown screws that are exactly the same and will interchange, but follow the directions on which to use.  I think they wanted the brown ones used when the brown wood is showing, but they will interchange anyway.  Just plan for 3 hours at least.

title: very pleased with all aspects of the product quality and assembly
text: I don't usually take the time to write a review of a product, but I read the reviews on products when I'm shopping online.  That's why I feel compelled to review the espresso kitchen.  My husband and I recently bought it for our granddaughter's second birthday and we were very, very pleased with all aspects of the product quality and assembly.  The kitchen itself is very well constructed. All materials were sturdy and made of good quality (keeping in mind it is a child's kitchen set). The assembly was time consuming but the instructions were fairly easy to follow and complete.  All parts were clearly labelled.  I would suggest opening the packet of hardware very carefully so the pieces don't get mixed up.  It took us about 3 1/2 hours to assemble but we took our time and followed all instructions carefully.  It's the perfect size for a two year old but I do think she'll be able to play with it for a few years.The best part is that our granddaughter loves it and plays with it every day!

title: Faucet broke at first use right after assembly
text:
First off, this is a beautiful looking play kitchen which was why we bought it in the first place.

Shipping was very fast and this arrived at 8am today (3 days ahead of scheduled delivery).

The kids were very excited for their new kitchen so my husband decided to assemble it before work. However:

- It was very time consuming to assemble. It took him a total of 2.5 hours to assemble.

- Once done, it was time to let the kids play with it. But the faucet broke within the first 5 minutes of my almost 3 year old playing with it.

You can imagine the disappointment, indeed. The main reason why I‚Äôm giving this 3 stars is because it looks gorgeous and it shipped fast. But I don‚Äôt think this item will last at all.

Amazon gave the option to return the item for a replacement or a full refund, but considering this took 2.5 hours to set up and will take another 2 or so hours to take down, repackage and ship back, we decided to go for the partial refund (which was not a lot). Going for the replacement option would be even worse cos it would require yet another 2.5 hours to set up the replacement when it arrives.

title: Great Kitchen, But Beware of Missing Parts!
text:
We were so excited to find this kitchen for our three-year old daughter for Christmas. We saw it in person at a friend's house and immediately ordered it. The box came slightly banged up, but we weren't surprised because of it's size/weight. On a whim, we decided to start putting it together a week before Christmas and THANK GOODNESS WE DID! When we first opened the box we found the directions were missing. We were able to find them online, which was a bit of a hassle, but a relief! When we started trying to put them together, things got really interesting. We found that the box was missing not one part, not two parts, but FIVE essential parts including the refrigerator door and the pole that keeps the whole kitchen upright.

I panicked because Christmas is only a week away and this is the only gift we were giving our daughter. Luckily, my husband was able to call the company and place an order online for free replacement parts. We just got a confirmation today that they overnighted them and they (should) arrive by Christmas. We were pleased with that aspect of the customer service experience, although I question how five essential parts could be missing from a fairly standard product.

Awesome kitchen, but beware: open and begin putting together well ahead of when you need it!

Update: Out of the 5 parts we ordered, they only sent 4 and Christmas is tomorrow. Bummed....

title: Broken On Arrival, Big Birthday Disappointment
text:
Rather than write a new review, I'm just going to copy and paste the email I wrote to KidKraft customer service after opening the box to discover a broken essential piece. Long story shirt, my son is going to be super disappointed on his birthday and this box full of a million pieces will (according to KidKraft's customer service email response) sit in my living room taking up space while we wait up to 4 weeks to get a new piece of crap particle board in the mail. Moral: yes, your kids will probably love this thing, but you open yourself up to the risk of receiving broken stuff and then having to wait a long time and jump through many hoops to resolve it.

To Whom It May Concern,

I ordered one of your kitchen sets from Amazon.com for my son's birthday. Much to my disappointment, one of the essential pieces arrived completely broken and will not allow me to put this set together for his special day.

Honestly, it's completely ridiculous that you put the onus on your customer to photograph and upload an image of a broken part and proof of purchase and furthermore that your customer service number does not take calls on weekends or after hours. Two parents with full time jobs should not have to deal with garbage like this. You think customers are trying to steal single random parts from you? The notion is absurd. It should be a simple phone call and a "yes sir or yes m'am we'll have that part overnighted to you right away".

I'm extremely busy and now won't have time to put this together for him until at least a week from now. This gigantic box will not also be taking up space in our only common area until then too. I would gladly return it if it weren't so cumbersome and impossible to repack.

If you cannot figure out how to package your products properly so that the shipping services don't break them before they arrive, you should not be selling them and creating these sad situations for families wherein a child is expecting an amazing present and then they can't even experience it at the appropriate time due to your negligence. And to add insult to injury make parents jump through additional hoops just to get a replacement part.

But instead I proceeded to go ahead and jumped through your hoops, wasting time on my son's birthday. And you have the audacity to just make it "standard shipping"? (note -- an automated reply email stated that it new takes up to 4 weeks for replacement parts).

I doubt I will be able to recommend your product to anyone based on this sub-par customer service experience and a big let down on my child's birthday.

To reiterate, if you can't pack or manufacture a piece of cheap particle board properly without it breaking, you should not be selling anything.

Thanks for screwing up what's supposed to be a 100% happy day.

Regretfully yours.

title: Beautiful kitchen, terrible assembly.
text:
We love the end result of this kitchen, but getting there was the biggest pain in the ass. We had several damaged and scratched pieces, but because we were painting everything, we weren‚Äôt too worried. However, had we not been painting the pieces, I would have been furious.

The directions are some of the worst directions I have ever followed. The pictures are not descriptive in which way pieces need to go. Some screws are silver and some are bronze. The directions never tell you which one to use so you have to make the decision on your own. Use the silver ones where you won‚Äôt see, and the bronze on the outside.

A LOT of our holes didn‚Äôt match up. We were having to force them in to get them to line up. The very top piece of the microwave does not match up to the rest and it looks ridiculous. We might try just shaving off the extra inch of overhang. Idk.

My takeaways: if you plan on painting the kitchen, it‚Äôs a good one to have. You can cover up the damage and you won‚Äôt see it. If you need a kitchen put together quickly and easily, find a different one. It‚Äôs beautiful once it‚Äôs together but my husband and I were ready to smash the whole thing before we were even halfway done.

title: Lost and found!
text: Bought this kitchen for my 2 1/2 year old granddaughter at our house. Chose this kitchen based on it's modern and realistic looks. Will say the lost part of this tale begins the moment I opened and unpacked the shipping box. The number of pieces and bolts was very overwhelming.  The pictured assembly instructions weren't very intuitive. I did persevere and after 6 hours finished assembly just in time for the princesses arrival. The found part of this story is the joy this kitchen brought to my little princess. I would recommend this item to anyone who is looking for a children's kitchen. You will need to ensure you keep all parts facing the correct direction during assembly, keep the channels for the back aligned this will help. Read several reviews saying holes didn't align, found if you ensure alignment before tightening everything fit. Be patient and don't get frustrated and the joy it will bring to your loved one will be well worth the time invested.

title: Best Christmas gift ever!
text:
LOVE this kitchen! Bought for 6 yr old and it was her fav Christmas gift. My child is a VERY tall 6 yr old and I purchased this product because this kitchen is taller than any other I have seen. Her older cousins have also enjoyed playing with it (boys and girls as old as 10 yrs).
I read reviews and they are right on... This will take 2 to 3 hours to put together and you will need 2 people. The directions are amazing. There are only black and white diagrams, but they are constructed in a way that no matter what language you speak, you can follow along. I suggest you look at the screw tips, some are silver and some are brown (to match the parts).
The final product looks like a beautiful piece of furniture, which was also important to me because we are keeping this in our family room. There is plenty of storage for her to keep her pots, pans, and food (sold separately) out of sight when not in use. A few adults and children have seen it and asked, "Can she really cook in that thing?". They are really thinking this is like the little ovens kids can bake in... The only negative is the phone, as one reviewer stated; it is VERY cheap looking, compared to the rest of the unit. Almost as if the person who designed the phone worked on a different project.
I would order other products from KidKraft without hesitation.

title: Workmanship on the overall design as well as the individual pieces are excellent. Assembly took ~ 90 minutes for two adults ...
text: This toy kitchen is a quality product. The kitchen came in a heavy box that contained all pieces carefully wrapped and cushioned with styro inserts - nothing was scratched or broken. Workmanship on the overall design as well as the individual pieces are excellent. Assembly took ~ 90 minutes for two adults (who had fun in the process). Each piece has a sticker with a part number on it and the assembly guide is easy to follow because the illustrations show the not only the piece but also the number of the part. Very unusual and excellent in the world of self-assembly furniture: All the hardware pieces, which were numerous, came in individually labeled bubble bins for each type of hardware. Nothing was missing; there were even some extra pieces, plus a kit to bolt the unit to a wall to guard against tipping over. The pieces were engineered such that they fit together perfectly. Attention to detail is great: switches that click when you turn them, a chalkboard, clear plastic windows for the microwave and oven doors, even a towel rack. The end product is a stylish kitchen (silver and espresso colors) with tons of play potential. Thumbs up!

title: Not what we expected...
text:
We bought this kitchen as the "big" birthday present for my 3 year old. The Friday before the Saturday party we went to assemble it and realized that the manufacturer did not send us piece #1, and we could not put it together. We had to go back to the manufacturer's website and request a replacement piece, which took over a week to arrive. It was sent without charge, but it was late enough to arrive that we did not have the kitchen together in time for the birthday party and could not give it as a present, which was very disappointing. If you order this item, check to make sure you have ALL pieces the moment it arrives and before beginning assembly. And give yourself 7-10 days to get a replacement if needed before you plan to use it.

When we finally got the piece #1, the assembly took 3 hours with two people. Just be aware that this is not an item you can assemble by yourself and it will take several hours.

It also does not look like the item in the picture. The version we received does not have the "back splash" with the knobs for kitchen tools. And the towel rack is part plastic (grey) and part wood (very light colored). It does not have the same appeal as what was pictured. Overall, it was a disappointing product.

text: I am thrilled with this kitchen. I have a 3.5 year old daughter and 2-year-old son. This kitchen is just the right size for them to play with together and not push and fight constantly. I selected it because I have a boy and girl and did not want to go with a pink kitchen, which so many of them are. I also love this kitchen for the details. The water/ice dispenser is not just a drawing as it is on so many kitchens. You can actually put a cup in there and pretend you are getting water. It has a phone which my kids love. My daughter "called" her Grandma and Papa who live in another state several times on Christmas morning to talk to them about the sandwich she was making Papa and the cookies she was making Grandma. The chalkboard is real and they have had fun writing on it. There is even a removable cutting board in the cabinet underneath the sink! I highly recommend the [[ASIN:B003BAN3AU KidKraft Metal Accessories Set]] with pots, pans, a ladle and spatula because the handles are big enough to go over the knobs on the "backsplash" and hang there.  My children have also loved the [[ASIN:B00146K0I6 Melissa & Doug Slice and Bake Cookie Set]], the [[ASIN:B00006JZCS Melissa & Doug Wooden Sandwich-Making Set]] and the [[ASIN:B000I8UK04 Plan Toys Assorted Fruits and Vegetables]]. This kitchen is great quality, a really good size for toddlers and preschoolers, and just a lot of fun!  I highly recommend it!

text: This kitchen is great for my 17 month old and she will grow with it!  A little painful to put together but worth it.

title: My daughter was very disappointed. If we were able to assemble it
text: The pre cut holes were not aligned to where the screws should go; as a result we could not put it together on Xmas eve and we had to send it back. My daughter was very disappointed. If we were able to assemble it, I think that it would have been a quality item. Read the reviews before you purchase this, especially read the comments about how tedious it is to put this together.

title: Wrong item entirely
text: I ordered this kitchen last year for my granddaughter, I sent it home with my daughter who lives in another town so I left it in the box assuming it was what I ordered, she sent me a picture when she put it together, I was mortified it wasn't even close to this product, hugely disappointed, should have sent it back but the hassle of that would have cost me more

title: Perfect little kitchen.
text: It was a bit tedious to put together.  However the manufacturers did a great job at labeling everything and they even included extra screws etc.

title: Sturdy! Very Real for a little one!
text: Came in a heavy box, took roughly 6-8 hours to put together with small breaks of course. Many pieces to assemble but it was all worth it. My kid loves it! It‚Äôs sturdy, durable and much like a mini ‚Äúreal life‚Äù gourmet kitchen. By far the best gift she received. It‚Äôs worth the money and assembly time!!!!

title: Fantastic, But took a long time to assemble.
text:
The finished product looks great, but if you're planning to have it ready when your kid wakes up as a surprise...better start early. It took almost 4 hours to assemble. It was easy, just a lot of parts and the manual took a bit of getting used to in terms of properly aligning the pieces and such. Could use better technical drawings. However, everything is very well marked/numbered/organized. Just a lot of assembly.
The kids love it and they're a bit older (7 & 3).

title: Outstanding condition after many kids!
text: I bought this year's ago for my daughter, she has since outgrown it but all the kids I have watched through out the years have loved it too! There are no missing parts or pieces and looks almost brand new still!! Kidkraft is an amazing brand!
